SUMMARY
Lebanon discards an estimated two to three million end-of-life tires per year (approximately 25,000–30,000 tonnes of rubber waste), yet possesses no industrial-scale upstream crumb-rubber capacity to feed the regional polymer-compounding economy. Re-Tire Lebanon is a Société à Responsabilité Limitée to be incorporated in the Keserwan-Matn industrial corridor, processing 1,500–3,000 tonnes of waste tires per year on a single-shift ambient-grinding line. Following a Q1 2026 primary-source interview with a Mount Lebanon polymer compounder (anonymised per Annex 1), the venture has pivoted from a downstream tile-manufacturing thesis to an upstream qualified-feedstock supply model: tile production locks rubber permanently into polyurethane binder, whereas mesh-graded crumb supplied to thermoplastic compounders serves footwear, automotive aftermarket, plastics, and specialty rubber applications on a genuinely circular path. Crumb pricing of USD 250–550 per tonne combined with steel by-product revenue (15 % yield) produces a unit economy in which steel sales alone cover monthly operating expenditure, converting crumb revenue into pure contribution margin. The four-phase roadmap moves from upstream feedstock supply, to rubberised-asphalt offtake on the USD 11 billion World Bank Lebanon reconstruction pipeline, to deeper compounder partnership, and ultimately to co-branded end-product launches by Year 5. Capital expenditure of USD 150,000–350,000 is structured as 60 % grant, 25 % founder and 15 % angel, at a Damodaran-derived weighted-average cost of capital of 30 % reflecting Lebanese country risk. The venture aligns with Lebanon's NDC 3.0 and captures upside from the EU Microplastics Regulation (EU 2023/2055) and Saudi Arabia's Vision 2030 infrastructure programme.
KEYWORDS
Circular economy; Crumb rubber; Tire recycling; Lebanon; Keserwan-Matn; Reverse logistics; Polymer compounding; Upstream feedstock; SARL; GAFTA; ESG; NDC 3.0; Vision 2030; EU 2023/2055.
