Chapter I: Introduction
Every business plan rests on a small number of foundational commitments that, once made, constrain every subsequent decision. This opening section makes those commitments explicit and submits each to a recognised analytical framework, so that the chapters that follow can interrogate market, competition, operations and finance without re-litigating first principles. Section 1.1 sets out the Team Charter; the three founders, their functional ownership, and the governance protocol that disciplines decision-making. Section 1.2 applies the Value Proposition Canvas (Osterwalder, Pigneur, Bernarda & Smith, 2014) to the venture's primary customer segment, mapping fit between customer jobs, pains and gains on one side and Re-Tire's pain relievers and gain creators on the other. Section 1.3 articulates the Vision Canvas, anchoring the ten-year horizon in measurable outcomes aligned with Lebanon's Climate Policy Package launched on 23 September 2025 (Republic of Lebanon, 2025; UNDP Lebanon, 2025). 
1.1  Team Charter
Re-Tire Lebanon is led by three Master of Business Administration candidates of the MBA(29) cohort at ESA Business School. The founding team is structured around three executive functions: technology and innovation, operations and finance, and commercial development, which map directly onto the venture's principal capability requirements. The composition is consistent with the new venture teams literature reviewed by Klotz, Hmieleski, Bradley and Busenitz (2014), which identifies the combination of functional diversity and shared operational orientation as a principal antecedent of team effectiveness in early-stage ventures; the related work of Beckman (2006) on prior firm affiliations further supports the team's mix of complementary professional backgrounds. The team operates under a written shareholder and decision-making protocol that codifies equity, vesting, decision rights and dispute-resolution procedures, and is consistent with the founder-contracting guidance of Wasserman (2012).
1.1.1  Functional Roles and Responsibilities
Michael Mrad serves as Chief Technology and Innovation Officer. He owns the venture's technology stack, process engineering and innovation pipeline. His remit covers specification of the five-machine ambient-grinding line, qualification of mesh-graded crumb output, research and development feasibility, and the data-analytics platform that will track feedstock quality, throughput and energy consumption in real time. He serves as the venture's technical interface with the anonymised polymer-compounding anchor customer.
Paul Tabet serves as Chief Operating Officer. He owns end-to-end operations, from inbound tire collection logistics through the production line to outbound dispatch. His remit also includes the financial-planning function and the working-capital discipline that the Lebanese banking environment makes a permanent operational priority rather than a periodic exercise.
Tony Rayes serves as Chief Commercial Officer. He owns the demand side of the business: client acquisition, partnership development, marketing execution, customer-relationship management and revenue generation. He leads the anchor-customer relationship and the specification-partner programme adapted for business-to-business industrial sales.
