1.3  Vision Canvas
The Vision Canvas articulates the long-horizon ambition of the venture in a format that converts directional aspiration into measurable outcome targets. It is organised in four sub-sections: the ten-year vision statement, the operational mission, the values that animate the venture, and the quantified ten-year targets against which performance will be measured. The structure follows Collins and Porras (1996), whose vision framework combines core ideology (core values and core purpose) with an envisioned future built around a “Big Hairy Audacious Goal” that is sufficiently bold to inspire effort yet sufficiently concrete to permit measurement.
1.3.1  Ten-Year Vision
Re-Tire's ten-year vision is to operate as the foundational upstream infrastructure of the Lebanese circular polymer economy, supplying qualified crumb-rubber feedstock to a constellation of downstream compounders, asphalt mixers, construction-materials producers and end-product manufacturers that use mesh-graded recycled rubber as raw material for their production. The vision is intentionally infrastructural rather than product-centric: the venture's strategic identity is to be the supply backbone on which a Lebanese circular-rubber ecosystem can be built, not to be the largest single producer of any one downstream product. This identity is consistent with the inner-loop logic of the Ellen MacArthur Foundation (2013) butterfly diagram, which prioritises material circulation at the highest retained value over linear extraction of any single downstream margin pool.
1.3.2  Operational Mission
The operational mission is to convert Lebanon's unmanaged waste-tire stream into qualified industrial feedstock for the circular polymer economy, starting with the Keserwan-Matn region. The first measurable expression of this mission is the diversion of at least four thousand tonnes per annum of end-of-life tires from open burning, dumping and landfill in the Keserwan-Matn region by Year 3 of operations. This diversion volume is approximately twenty per cent of the estimated regional waste-tire generation of twenty to twenty-five thousand tonnes per year, derived by proportional allocation of the national twenty-five thousand tonne baseline (Mrad & El-Samra, 2020) to the Keserwan-Matn share of the national vehicle fleet. Achieving this volume by Year 3 generates quantified avoided-emissions outcomes that contribute to Lebanon's twenty-two per cent unconditional and thirty-three per cent conditional greenhouse-gas emission reduction targets by 2035, set out in the third Nationally Determined Contribution (NDC 3.0) launched as part of the Climate Policy Package on 23 September 2025 (Republic of Lebanon, 2025; United Nations Development Programme Lebanon, 2025).
1.3.3  Core Values
Three values animate the venture and are codified in the founder shareholder agreement as cultural commitments enforceable through the leaver provisions. The first is radical transparency on financial and environmental data, including monthly public disclosure of throughput, energy consumption, avoided-emissions and worker-safety metrics on the company website. The second is no-bribe operations, consistent with the corruption-resistant governance standards endorsed for the MENA region by the OECD Anti-Bribery Convention framework, under which any payment outside the published contractual rate to any public official or counterparty is grounds for immediate dismissal and forfeiture of unvested equity. The third is explicit honesty about the limits of circularity at every stage of the value chain: the team will not overclaim circular outcomes that cannot be substantiated by primary measurement, and will publicly correct any external claim made about the venture that exceeds verifiable evidence. The three values together respond to the structural credibility deficit that Lebanese ventures face in the post-2019 environment, where opacity and self-serving claim inflation have been principal drivers of investor and customer distrust.
1.3.4  Quantified Ten-Year Targets
The quantified ten-year vision targets are set out in Table 1.3 and operationalized through the Phased Roadmap of Section 1.6. The targets are calibrated against Lebanon's NDC 3.0 mitigation pathway (Republic of Lebanon, 2025) and against the regional demand pull modelled in Chapter II. 
