Key Partnerships
Anchor compounder; truck-fleet operators; tire-shop network of 40–60 nodes; municipalities of Keserwan and Matn; Berytech; UNDP Lebanon Green Investment Facility; Association of Lebanese Industrialists.
Cost Structure
Equipment depreciation; LBP-anchored labour cost ceiling (Decree 699/2025 minimum-wage floor); USD-pegged diesel and electricity; consumables; insurance; logistics.

1.4.1  Observations on the v1.0 Canvas
Three observations on the canvas merit narrative emphasis. First, the customer-segment block is deliberately concentrated on a single anchor in Phase 1, with a small constellation of secondary buyers. This concentration is the central commercial risk of the plan, addressed extensively in Chapter IX, but it is also the design choice that makes the venture viable at startup scale, because compounder-grade qualification cycles last three to six months per customer and a wider initial customer base would dilute the team's sales bandwidth below the threshold required to win any single qualification. Second, the revenue-streams block captures the single most consequential primary-source insight from the field interview: steel by-product revenue is sized at a level that covers monthly operating expenditure, which converts the crumb-rubber sales line into pure contribution margin and capital-recovery cash flow, a structural feature of the unit economics analysed in Chapter VIII. Third, the key-partnerships block lists Berytech and the UNDP Lebanon Green Investment Facility as partners rather than as financiers, reflecting the team's view that the relationship in question is genuinely strategic and operational rather than purely transactional.

Chapter II: The Market Research Toolbox
This chapter applies the market research toolbox to validate the demand-side assumptions underpinning the venture and to assemble the evidentiary basis for the v2.0 Business Model Canvas of Chapter III. It follows the sequence prescribed by the Lean Business Plan methodology. Section 2.1 defines and segments the market. Section 2.2 applies a PESTEL macro-environmental scan, including an extended deep dive on the Lebanese-specific variables that dominate risk-adjusted returns. Section 2.3 analyses demand, defines the venture’s targets, and models organisational buying behaviour. Section 2.4 maps the competitive landscape through Porter’s Five Forces, competitor benchmarking, market-position classification, and a positioning map. Section 2.5 concludes the toolbox with a TAM-SAM-SOM triangulation of market size. Section 2.6 consolidates the analysis into a SWOT inventory and a TOWS strategic-matching matrix.
2.1  Market Definition
Re-Tire Lebanon competes in the Lebanese and regional Middle East and North Africa (MENA) crumb-rubber feedstock market. Market definition is the first instrument of the toolbox because every subsequent analysis, macro-environmental scanning, demand quantification, competitor mapping, and market sizing, depends on a precise statement of the economic sector, the geography, the product, and the customer the venture intends to serve. A vague market definition produces a vague business plan; a precise one disciplines every figure that follows.
2.1.1  Industry and Economic Sector
The relevant economic sector is the upstream raw-material layer of the recycled-rubber value chain. It is best understood as the qualified-feedstock tier that supplies three distinct downstream chains: polymer compounding for footwear, automotive aftermarket, plastics, and specialty rubber applications; rubberised-asphalt and road infrastructure; and sports-surfacing, playground, and animal-husbandry flooring. The sector is defined by mesh-grade specifications consistent with ASTM Standard D5603, with particle-size distribution determined per ASTM Standard D5644 (ASTM International, 2023a, 2023b); by purity thresholds for residual metal and textile fibre; by United States dollar-anchored pricing; and by the existence of qualified industrial buyers willing to transact under formal Certificate of Analysis discipline. Re-Tire Lebanon positions itself deliberately at this upstream tier rather than in any single downstream product category. This choice is foundational: it defines the venture as an industrial input supplier whose customers are themselves manufacturers, and it is the choice whose strategic rationale is developed in full in Chapter III.
Viewed through a circular-economy lens, the sector occupies the point at which a waste stream is converted back into a productive raw material, closing a loop that currently terminates in open burning or uncontrolled dumping. This framing is more than rhetorical: it determines which buyers, regulators, and financiers regard the venture as relevant. It places Re-Tire Lebanon within the priority Extended Producer Responsibility stream of Law 80/2018, within the scope of the Climate Policy Package examined in Section 2.2.5, and within the explicit mandate of the circular-economy grant facilities surveyed in Section 2.2.7. The economic sector is therefore best defined not merely as rubber recycling but as qualified secondary-raw-material supply, a definition that aligns the venture with the policy and finance environment on which its capital structure depends.
2.1.2  Geographic Scope
The venture’s addressable geography is defined in three concentric rings. The innermost ring is Lebanon itself, where the venture operates from a Keserwan-Matn facility within 30 kilometres of the anchor customer’s pilot facility and within 60 kilometres of the Beirut and Tripoli ports. Proximity is a deliberate competitive instrument here, not an accident of incorporation: it is what permits the sub-seven-day domestic lead time that imported granulate cannot match. The middle ring is the Greater Arab Free Trade Area (GAFTA) zone of 17 Arab member states (League of Arab States, 1997), accessible duty-free for crumb rubber under Harmonised System Chapter 40 since the agreement’s full tariff elimination on 1 January 2005. The outermost ring is the broader MENA region, including non-GAFTA markets such as Türkiye and Iran, which are accessible but subject to standard tariff and non-tariff barriers and are therefore secondary in commercial planning. This three-ring structure is the basis of the Serviceable Addressable Market constraint applied in Section 2.5.
2.1.3  Product Scope
The product scope is mesh-graded crumb rubber in the 20-mesh, and 30-mesh fractions, marketed as SKUs RC-20, and RC-30, produced by ambient-grinding technology. Coarser fractions below 20 mesh are produced as intermediate outputs but are not sold as finished products in Phase 1: their market is dominated by tire-derived-fuel (TDF) applications priced at USD 30–70 per tonne, too low to support the venture’s unit economics. Finer fractions above 30 mesh are not produced in Phase 1 because they require cryogenic-grinding technology reserved for Phase 3 capital deployment. Steel by-product, in the form of recovered tire-bead and tread wire, is sold as a separate product line under the designation Re-Tire RC-Steel; its significance is disproportionate to its tonnage, because steel revenue is sized to cover monthly operating expenditure. Textile-fibre by-product is currently treated as a process residue with negligible commercial value but is monitored for emerging applications in the Phase 3 timeframe.
2.1.4  Customer Scope and Segmentation
Customer segmentation follows a four-tier structure that mirrors the B2B account-management framework of Chapter IV. The tiers are defined by annual feedstock requirement and by the technical sophistication of the supplier-qualification process each customer imposes, as summarised in Table 2.1.

