2.3  Demand Analysis
Demand analysis answers the toolbox’s central commercial question: who will buy, how the venture will reach them, how they decide, and how many units can be sold at what price. The analysis distinguishes primary-source-validated Lebanese demand from the larger but less certain regional demand, models the organisational buying process, and concludes with the segment-selection decision.
2.3.1  Target Definition: Who Will Buy
The venture’s buyers are industrial firms, not individual consumers, which means demand is concentrated, relationship-driven, and contractually formalised rather than diffuse and transactional. Three target archetypes are addressed, in descending order of Phase 1 priority. The first is the industrial polymer compounder, the anchor segment, which buys mesh-graded crumb as a continuous-production raw material and qualifies suppliers through a formal three-to-six-month protocol. The second is the asphalt project manager and road contractor, who buys asphalt-rubber binder feedstock against tendered reconstruction projects and whose demand is therefore lumpy and tender-driven. The third is the sports-surfacing installer, who buys infill and base material for athletic tracks, playgrounds, and gym flooring. Each archetype is reached through direct B2B account management and founder-led senior-relationship selling rather than through mass marketing, consistent with the channel design of Chapter IV.
2.3.2  Lebanese Demand
Lebanese demand is anchored by the anonymised polymer-compounding partner’s stated annual feedstock requirement of 600–1,200 tonnes (Primary-source interview, 2026, anonymised per Annex 1), a primary-source data point that materially de-risks the Phase 1 commercial plan because it converts an assumed market into a substantially contracted one. This single figure is the most valuable evidence in the chapter: it is the difference between a plan that hopes for demand and one that has measured it. Beyond the anchor customer, the rubberised-asphalt overlay potential implied by the USD 11 billion reconstruction pipeline is substantial: at a 0.5–2% crumb-by-mass loading across an estimated 5,000 kilometres of damaged road, demand could exceed 5,000 tonnes per year at full deployment, well above the venture’s Phase 1 capacity, which means the constraint in Phase 2 is production rather than demand. Sports-surfacing demand from Lebanese clubs and schools is estimated at 200–500 tonnes per year, based on a bottom-up count of fitness facilities, school playgrounds, and athletic facilities.
2.3.3  Regional Demand
Regional demand is anchored by Saudi Arabia’s stadium and athletic-track build-out for the FIFA 2034 World Cup, which commits to 15 stadiums across five host cities, Riyadh, Jeddah, Al Khobar, Abha, and NEOM, with 11 entirely new venues and four renovations (FIFA, 2024). Embedded synthetic-surfacing and rubberised-asphalt demand across the stadiums, the associated transport infrastructure, and the surrounding Vision 2030 entertainment districts, Qiddiya, NEOM, and Diriyah Gate, implies multi-thousand-tonne demand over the build-out window. The United Arab Emirates Tadweer Gulf Rubber Factory at Al Ain operated at approximately 10,400 tonnes per year against a 24,000-tonne nameplate capacity; the gap between throughput and nameplate, plus broader regional under-capacity, is potentially accessible to imported qualified crumb that carries a GAFTA Certificate of Origin. Egypt’s cement-sector TDF-substitution potential is large in volume terms but is explicitly not targeted, because TDF pricing falls below the venture’s unit-economics threshold. Regional demand is therefore real and large, but it is treated as Phase 2–3 upside rather than Phase 1 base case, because it is not yet contracted.
2.3.4  Organisational Buyer Behaviour
Because the venture’s customers are organisations rather than individuals, the buying decision is best understood through an organisational adaptation of the consumer-behaviour model. Three clusters of variables shape an industrial purchase. Functional variables dominate: a compounder’s procurement decision rests on whether the feedstock holds mesh tolerance batch to batch, clears contaminant thresholds, and arrives on schedule, attributes that are measured, not felt. Organisational variables are the analogue of social influence: the procurement officer answers to a production manager who answers to the firm’s own customers, so a supplier who lets the buyer pass a credible sustainability story upstream is selected over one who cannot. Situational variables, an import delayed by correspondent-banking friction, a rejected batch halting a production line, frequently trigger the search for a new supplier in the first place. The decisive behavioural feature is that the purchase is not a single event but a staged process: a qualification sample, then a trial order, and only then a multi-year offtake agreement. This staging rewards a supplier who can demonstrate consistency early and cheaply, and it is the reason the venture treats the first 50–100 tonnes of anchor-customer volume as a qualification investment rather than as a profit centre.
2.3.5  What Industrial Customers Want: The Five Fs
The lean-planning toolbox frames customer requirements through the “five Fs.” Re-Tire Lebanon’s value proposition is deliberately engineered against each, as Table 2.3 sets out. The framing is useful because it forces the venture to express its offer in the buyer’s terms rather than its own.
