2.3.7  Demand Risks and Sensitivities
A demand analysis is incomplete without an honest account of what would cause the demand to fail to materialise. Three sensitivities dominate. The first is anchor-customer dependence: the 600–1,200-tonne figure rests on a single firm, and a change in that firm’s own end-market, ownership, or import economics would directly compress Phase 1 revenue. This is the demand-side mirror of the buyer-power force of Section 2.4.1, and it is the reason the plan commits to seeding three-to-five Tier-2 buyers within Year 1 rather than treating diversification as a later convenience. The second is the timing of the reconstruction pipeline: the rubberised-asphalt opportunity is real in scale but contingent on tender disbursement, and a slippage in donor funding or in Council for Development and Reconstruction procurement would delay the Phase 2 revenue rather than cancel it. The plan treats this asymmetrically, the reconstruction channel is upside in the base case, not a load-bearing assumption. The third is price sensitivity: the venture’s 15–40% landed-cost advantage over imports is the demand-pull mechanism, and a sustained fall in global virgin-rubber or import-granulate prices would narrow that gap. The mitigation is the venture’s structurally low cost base, which preserves a positive margin even under significant price compression, and the non-price advantages, lead time, origin, traceability, that do not erode when import prices fall.
The overall demand picture is therefore robust but not unconditional: it is anchored by one validated contract, supported by a quantified domestic segment, and surrounded by a large but explicitly discounted regional upside. Presenting it this way, base case, upside, and named risks kept separate, is itself a discipline the financial model of Chapter VIII inherits.
2.4  Competition Analysis and Positioning
Competition analysis identifies the venture’s competitors and substitutes, assesses their advantages and disadvantages, and establishes the basis for a defensible competitive position. The analysis proceeds through Porter’s Five Forces, a competitor and substitute inventory, a benchmarking framework, a market-position classification, an industry life-cycle assessment, and a positioning map.
2.4.1  Porter’s Five Forces
Porter’s (1979) Five Forces framework assesses the structural attractiveness of the upstream crumb-rubber feedstock industry. The threat of new entrants is medium-low: capital expenditure of USD 150,000–350,000 sits below the threshold that attracts opportunistic entrants but above what bootstrap operators can access in current Lebanese banking conditions, while permit complexity and the three-to-six-month customer-qualification cycle create an entry latency that cannot realistically be compressed below 90 days. The bargaining power of suppliers is low: tire feedstock is a negative-cost input, since tire shops, vulcanisers, and municipalities currently pay for disposal or dump informally, and grinding equipment is multi-sourced globally across Eldan, Forrec, Genox, and Granutech-Saturn. The bargaining power of buyers is high and is the single largest commercial risk in the plan: Phase 1 concentration on one anchor compounder is mitigated contractually through multi-year offtake agreements with volume floors, by diversification into three-to-five secondary buyers in Year 1, and strategically by the Phase 2 rubberised-asphalt channel, which diversifies industry exposure entirely. The threat of substitutes is medium: virgin synthetic rubber and imported Chinese and Turkish granulate are direct substitutes, defended against by a 15–30% landed-cost advantage and the GAFTA Certificate of Origin. Industry rivalry is low and has been reclassified post-pivot: firms that would have competed for downstream tile customers under the original thesis, M.S. Sport, Leaders Group, Sigma Group, Atris Engineering, and Transtrade, become prospective customers under the upstream-supply model. Table 2.5 summarises the assessment.
