2.4.2  Direct and Indirect Competitors
Direct competitors in Lebanon are limited to a small set of informal shredders producing coarse rubber chips and granules, none of whom publicly disclose mesh-graded output with batch-level Certificates of Analysis. Field reconnaissance by the founder team in 2025 identified three such operators in Mount Lebanon, all operating below 500 tonnes per year and none supplying compounder-grade material; they are best understood as feedstock-sourcing competitors, rivals for waste-tire supply, rather than product competitors. A small Baawerta-based operator is the only directory-listed tile-and-sheet manufacturer in the Aley district (Kompass Lebanon, 2024); under the upstream pivot, such operators are reclassified as prospective downstream customers. Indirect competitors are imported-granulate suppliers from Türkiye, China, and Eastern Europe, whose landed prices range from USD 450 to 700 per tonne with six-to-ten-week lead times. These suppliers operate at scale with cost structures that cannot be matched per unit, but they are systematically disadvantaged by lead time, by FATF-related correspondent-banking friction, and by the absence of a Lebanese-origin certificate that would qualify their material for GAFTA duty-free re-export. The venture does not attempt to beat imports on unit cost; it competes on the dimensions imports cannot serve.
Two further features of the competitive set deserve emphasis. First, the absence of any incumbent that combines quality discipline with domestic presence means the venture is not displacing an entrenched competitor but occupying genuinely vacant ground; the competitive task is to establish a new category standard rather than to win share from a defender. Second, the most economically rational competitive response the venture should anticipate is not a domestic price war, the informal shredders lack the capital to qualify compounder-grade material, but a defensive reaction from importers, who may shorten quoted lead times or extend credit terms once a credible local supplier emerges. The venture’s structural defences against that reaction, namely GAFTA origin, currency-friction elimination, and physical proximity, are not easily neutralised by an importer, which is what makes the positioning durable rather than merely first.
2.4.3  Competitive Benchmarking
Benchmarking converts competitor analysis from a static description into a continuous-improvement discipline: it asks not only where the venture stands today but how it should systematically close the gap to best-in-class performers. Five complementary benchmarking modes are adopted, summarised in Table 2.6. The benchmarking plan that operationalises them, selecting variables, choosing best-in-class comparators, collecting data, comparing on a spider diagram, identifying gaps, and recalibrating, is embedded in the continuous-improvement system of Chapter V, so that benchmarking is a recurring management routine rather than a one-off planning exercise.
