2.4.7  Sources of Sustainable Competitive Advantage
Identifying a competitive position is necessary but not sufficient; the toolbox also asks whether the position can be defended over time. Re-Tire Lebanon’s competitive advantage rests on four sources, deliberately chosen because each is difficult for a competitor to replicate quickly. The first is a structural cost position: negative-cost feedstock, LBP-anchored labour, and a solar-photovoltaic energy hedge together produce a cost base that an importer cannot match and that a domestic entrant could match only by reproducing the same capital and energy decisions. The second is location and origin: physical proximity to Lebanese buyers and a GAFTA Certificate of Origin are advantages that cannot be acquired by a foreign competitor at any price, because they are properties of where the venture is incorporated and operates. The third is qualification lock-in: once a compounder has invested three to six months in qualifying Re-Tire as a supplier and has integrated its mesh grades into a production recipe, the switching cost it faces becomes a barrier protecting the incumbent supplier, the same buyer-power dynamic that is a threat before qualification becomes a defence after it. The fourth is reputational and relational capital: a documented Certificate-of-Analysis track record, an assured ESG-reporting routine, and a senior-level anchor relationship compound over time into trust that a new entrant cannot simply purchase.
These advantages are not equally durable. The cost position is the most exposed, because regional competitors in lower-cost or energy-subsidised jurisdictions could in principle undercut it; this is why the venture treats cost as a necessary condition rather than the core of its strategy. The origin, lock-in, and reputational advantages are more durable, and the strategic intent of the phased roadmap is to convert the early cost-based advantage into these stickier relational and certification-based advantages before regional competition intensifies. Sustained advantage, in other words, is treated as something the venture builds over the plan horizon rather than something it possesses at launch.
2.5  Market-Sizing Conclusion: TAM-SAM-SOM
The Lean Business Plan toolbox concludes with a TAM-SAM-SOM triangulation that converts the preceding analysis into a quantified statement of market size and obtainable share. For Re-Tire Lebanon the triangulation is constructed from three independent estimation paths, demand-side market sizing, supply-side waste-tire calibration, and strategic-pull projection from named regional infrastructure programmes, which are then cross-validated against one another and against the Lebanese sub-market. Using three independent paths is deliberate: a single estimate in a data-poor environment is a guess, whereas three converging estimates are a defensible figure.
2.5.1  Total Addressable Market
From the demand side, the MENA region captures an estimated 4–6% of global rubber demand, implying a regional rubber-input market of approximately USD 1.6–2.9 billion, of which crumb-rubber feedstock represents an estimated 5–10%, a TAM band of USD 80–290 million per year. From the supply side, aggregating documented MENA waste-tire arising, Lebanon at approximately 25,000 tonnes per year per Mrad and El-Samra (2020); Saudi Arabia at 170,000–210,000 tonnes; Egypt at 218,000–450,000 tonnes; and the United Arab Emirates, Jordan, and Iraq at smaller or less reliably documented volumes, yields approximately 600,000–900,000 tonnes per year; at a 60% crumb yield and an export ASP of USD 350 per tonne, this implies a TAM of approximately USD 210 million. From the strategic-pull angle, Saudi Vision 2030 giga-project contracts totalled USD 196 billion by October 2025 (Knight Frank, 2025), with a defined FIFA 2034 stadium build-out generating embedded crumb demand through running tracks, safety surfacing, and rubberised urban roads. The three paths converge on a Total Addressable Market of USD 200–300 million per year, which is the figure used in strategic planning.
2.5.2  Serviceable Addressable Market
The Serviceable Addressable Market is constrained by GAFTA duty-free reach, by Lebanese export logistics, principally the capacity and reliability of the Beirut and Tripoli ports, and by product-quality realism. The venture’s Phase 1 range is 20-to-30-mesh ambient-grade crumb, which excludes cryogenic micronised-powder markets and locked-in OEM tire-compounder contracts demanding fully traceable virgin-equivalent specifications. The realistic Serviceable Addressable Market therefore covers rubberised-asphalt premix, sports-surfacing infill subject to the EU Microplastics transition discussed in Section 2.2.5, and entry-level thermoplastic-elastomer compounding feedstock, estimated at USD 40–60 million per year.
2.5.3  Serviceable Obtainable Market
The venture’s three-year obtainable share is bounded by single-shift production capacity of approximately 3,000 tonnes per year at 60–70% Overall Equipment Effectiveness, and by the competitive intensity of the segment. At a blended ASP of USD 400 per tonne for crumb plus USD 250 per tonne for steel by-product at 15% yield, mature-state revenue is approximately USD 1.4 million per year. This represents 0.5–1% of the TAM and 2–4% of the SAM, a deliberately conservative SOM consistent with a Phase 1 thesis of pure upstream supply rather than aggressive market-share capture. A modest SOM is a feature of the plan, not a limitation of ambition: it keeps the venture below the political-attention threshold and within a financeable capital structure. Table 2.8 summarises the triangulation.
Table 2.8  TAM-SAM-SOM triangulation summary (USD per year)
Layer
Value (USD/yr)
Triangulation Basis
TAM — MENA crumb feedstock
200–300 million
Mordor Intelligence (2026a–c); MENA waste-tire ≈ 1M t/y × 60% yield × USD 350/t; Vision 2030 strategic pull
SAM — 10–30 mesh ambient, GAFTA-reachable
40–60 million
