2.5.4  Earlyvangelists: The First Customers
The lean-planning toolbox distinguishes the obtainable market from its sharpest leading edge, the earlyvangelists, the first customers who feel the problem most acutely, know they have it, and are willing to buy and co-develop a still-maturing solution rather than wait for a proven one. For Re-Tire Lebanon the principal earlyvangelist is the anchor polymer compounder: it already imports granulate at USD 450–700 per tonne, already absorbs FATF-related banking friction on every shipment, and has already articulated, in the primary-source interview, an explicit willingness to qualify a local supplier. A second earlyvangelist cohort is the small set of sports-surfacing installers and Lebanese road contractors who are most exposed to import lead times and most attracted to a Lebanese-origin sustainability story. Identifying earlyvangelists precisely matters because it tells the venture where to spend its first and scarcest sales effort: not across the whole SAM, but on the few buyers whose pain is acute enough to make them collaborators in Phase 1 qualification.
2.5.5  Lebanese Sub-Market
Lebanon generates an estimated two to three million waste tires per year, 25,000 to 30,000 tonnes, per Mrad and El-Samra (2020). Keserwan and Matn together are estimated to capture 4,000–5,000 tonnes per year, representing 15–20% of the national fleet; this estimate is justified by Mount Lebanon Governorate’s approximately 50% share of national population, its 58% share of registered industrial firms, and its dense automotive-dealership concentration. The Lebanese Serviceable Obtainable Market at the 1,500-to-3,000-tonne single-shift operating scale is approximately USD 0.4–0.6 million in crumb sales plus USD 0.1–0.2 million in steel by-product. The Lebanese sub-market is small in absolute terms, but it is sufficient to absorb the venture’s entire Phase 1 output and to fund the credibility needed for the regional expansion of later phases.
Data Gap: governorate-level waste-tire data. No governorate-level vehicle-registry breakdown is publicly available in Lebanon, and the country’s last general population census remains the 1932 enumeration. The 4,000–5,000 tonnes per year estimate for Keserwan-Matn must therefore be confirmed bottom-up through tire-shop and garage surveys conducted in the Year 0 pre-launch period, with the throughput target re-baselined against measured data thereafter.
2.6  SWOT and TOWS Synthesis
The market research toolbox concludes by consolidating its findings into a SWOT inventory, the internal Strengths and Weaknesses and the external Opportunities and Threats surfaced by the PESTEL, demand, and competition analyses, and then converting that inventory into actionable strategy through the TOWS strategic-matching matrix of Weihrich (1982). The distinction matters: SWOT lists, while TOWS decides.
2.6.1  SWOT Inventory
Table 2.9 sets out the SWOT inventory. The internal factors derive principally from the team charter and business model of Chapter I and the competition analysis of Section 2.4; the external factors derive from the PESTEL scan of Section 2.2 and the demand analysis of Section 2.3.
