Drawing the toolbox together, the chapter supports a clear market-readiness judgement. The market is defined and reachable; the macro-environment, on balance, favours the venture, with its threats concentrated in the financial domain the capital structure is built to absorb; demand is anchored by a primary-source contract rather than an assumption; the competitive quadrant the venture targets is genuinely uncontested; and the obtainable market, though deliberately modest, is sufficient to fund Phase 1 and the credibility required for later phases. The principal residual uncertainties, governorate-level feedstock data, anchor-customer concentration, and reconstruction-tender timing, are named explicitly rather than assumed away, and each is assigned a mitigation carried into a later chapter. On the toolbox’s own “right time” test, the evidence indicates that the market is ready and the timing window is open but finite.
The findings of this chapter, the four-tier customer segmentation, the opportunity-weighted PESTEL scan, the primary-source-validated demand, the staged organisational buying process, the post-pivot competitive inversion, and the conservative TAM-SAM-SOM triangulation, provide the evidentiary basis for the refinement of the Business Model Canvas from its v1.0 to its v2.0 specification in Chapter III.
Chapter III: Business Model Fine-Tuning
Chapter III applies Professor Elhage’s business-model fine-tuning lens, the sequential testing of the v1.0 Business Model Canvas of Chapter I against four external-force families: key trends, competition forces, demand forces, and macro-economic forces (Osterwalder & Pigneur, 2010). The market evidence assembled in Chapter II is used to interrogate each canvas block and to produce a refined v2.0 specification. Four forces drive the refinement. The key-trends force, the maturing circular-economy procurement norm (Ellen MacArthur Foundation, 2013), the EU Microplastics Regulation (EU) 2023/2055, and the 86% fall in Lebanese solar-PV cost since 2011 (LCEC, 2025), adds ISO 9001/14001 readiness to the value proposition and a 100–150 kWp solar installation to key resources. The competition force confirms the post-pivot inversion of Chapter II: former tile competitors are recoded as prospective customers, sharpening the customer-segments and key-partnerships blocks. The demand force, the anchor compounder’s validated 600–1,200-tonne requirement and the reconstruction-pipeline pull (World Bank, 2025), codifies multi-year offtake agreements and adds a Phase 2 rubberised-asphalt channel. The macro-economic force, banking-system closure, the Damodaran (2026) country-risk anchor, and the Decree 699 wage ceiling, fixes the 60% grant / 25% founder / 15% angel capital structure and the LBP-anchored labour cost into the cost-structure block.
Table 3.1 records the resulting v1.0→v2.0 refinements. The fine-tuned canvas yields six governing insights carried into the remainder of the plan: customer concentration is the central design discipline; steel by-product covers monthly operating expenditure and converts crumb revenue into pure contribution margin; GAFTA-origin export share is the country-risk hedge; solar PV is the highest-return capital tranche; the reform window is time-limited, so Phase 2 readiness must be built during Phase 1; and ASTM-anchored quality discipline is the one defensible moat. Chapter IV operationalises this refined canvas into the contemporary marketing plan.
