Chapter IV: Contemporary Marketing Plan
The contemporary marketing plan operationalises the v2.0 Business Model Canvas of Chapter III into concrete marketing decisions. It follows the five-component structure of the Lean Business Plan methodology, product and branding, price, promotion, place, and selling strategies, the classical marketing-mix articulation of McCarthy (1960) extended for the digital era by the Marketing 4.0 framework of Kotler, Kartajaya and Setiawan (2017). Section 4.1 specifies the product and the brand. Section 4.2 sets price against the price-quality matrix and a defined pricing strategy. Section 4.3 designs the promotion programme around the five-A customer path and explicit communication objectives. Section 4.4 addresses place, the distribution channel and the factors governing its choice. Section 4.5 sets out the selling strategy, the sales-force structure, and the B2B account-management framework. Throughout, the plan recognises that Re-Tire Lebanon sells an industrial input to organisational buyers, so the contemporary marketing toolkit is applied in its business-to-business rather than its consumer form.
One framing point governs the whole chapter. The contemporary marketing plan is best understood as three concentric layers: the offer itself, expressed through the four Ps; the way that offer is communicated, increasingly through the digital four Cs; and the relationship the offer builds over time, expressed through the four Es of brand experience and engagement. A venture that addresses only the first layer has a product but not a market position. The plan that follows is therefore organised so that each of the five components contributes to all three layers.
A second framing point concerns what the chapter must guard against. The lean-planning methodology is explicit that a marketing plan fails when it relies on empty claims and superlatives, when it is padded into a long document that obscures its own logic, and when it is not disciplined by evidence. This chapter is written against those failure modes: every claim is tied to a primary-source figure, an external benchmark, or a cited framework; every number is one a reviewer can interrogate; and the five components are kept distinct so that the argument of each is legible. The marketing plan is, in that sense, a continuation of the same evidentiary discipline that governed the market research of Chapter II, applied now to the venture’s own commercial decisions rather than to the external environment.
4.1  Product and Branding
The product component of the marketing mix answers a deceptively simple question: what, precisely, is the customer buying? For an industrial-feedstock venture the answer is not only the physical material but the description, design, benefits, additional services, quality assurance, and brand that accompany it. Each is specified below.
4.1.1  Product Description and the Three SKUs
The product is mesh-graded crumb rubber, offered in three stock-keeping units defined by particle-size fraction.  Re-Tire RC-20 is the twenty-mesh fraction at approximately 0.85 mm, used for athletic surfacing and entry-level compounding. Re-Tire RC-30 is the thirty-mesh fraction at approximately 0.6 mm, the premium fraction used for indoor athletic surfaces, moulded products, and high-specification compounding feedstock. Each SKU is delivered in one-tonne flexible intermediate bulk containers and accompanied by a batch-tagged Certificate of Analysis stating mesh distribution, moisture content, residual metal, and residual fibre, classified per ASTM Standard D5603 and tested for particle-size distribution per ASTM Standard D5644 (ASTM International, 2023a, 2023b). A defined three-SKU range, rather than an undifferentiated “rubber crumb” offer, is itself a marketing decision: it lets each downstream application be matched to a named product and a published price, and it gives the sales conversation a concrete vocabulary.
A fourth product line, Re-Tire RC-Steel, comprises the recovered tire-bead and tread wire separated during grinding. It is sold to Lebanese steel mills against London Metal Exchange Heavy Melt Steel No. 1 spreads. Although modest in tonnage, RC-Steel is strategically central: as established in Chapter III, steel revenue is sized to cover monthly operating expenditure, which converts the crumb lines into pure contribution margin. Textile-fibre by-product is treated as a process residue with negligible Phase 1 commercial value and is monitored for emerging applications in Phase 3.
4.1.2  Design, Benefits, and the Final Offer
In an industrial-feedstock context, “design” is not aesthetic but specification design, the deliberate engineering of mesh tolerances, contaminant ceilings, and packaging so that the product integrates predictably into a customer’s production recipe. The design choices that constitute the Re-Tire offer are a tolerance of plus or minus five percent on oversized particles, moisture at or below 0.75%, residual metal at or below 0.1%, and residual fibre at or below 0.5%, each verified per batch. The benefits that follow from these design choices, expressed in the customer’s own terms, are summarised in Table 4.1. The table is the venture’s “final offer” statement: value proposition, description, design, major benefits, quality, and a forward development commitment, assembled in one view.
Table 4.1  The final offer — Re-Tire Lebanon’s product proposition
Offer Element
Re-Tire Lebanon Specification
Value proposition
