4.1.3  Additional Services and the Quality Dimension
The lean-planning toolbox treats additional services, after-sale support and delivery in particular, as part of the product, not separate from it. For Re-Tire Lebanon three additional services are integral to the offer. The first is the Certificate of Analysis issued with every shipment, which is simultaneously a quality instrument and a marketing asset, because it gives the buyer documentation it can pass to its own customers. The second is optional door-to-door logistics offered at cost-plus pricing, which removes a friction for buyers without their own inbound fleet. The third is the co-formulation pilot programme, reserved for Phase 2 onward, through which the venture works with a customer to develop a bespoke mesh blend, a service that deepens the relationship and raises the switching cost. Quality, the customer-satisfaction triad of quality, delivery, and cost, is the dimension on which the venture has chosen to compete: the plan does not promise the lowest price, but it promises the most consistently specified and most reliably delivered product in its segment.
4.1.4  Brand Architecture
Brand architecture, following Aaker (1996) and Kapferer (2012), defines how the venture’s brands relate to one another. Re-Tire Lebanon adopts a deliberately conservative endorsed-brand structure. “Re-Tire Lebanon” is the corporate master brand, expressing three ideas: genuine circularity, Lebanese origin, and industrial discipline. The product range, RC-20, RC-30, and RC-Steel, functions as an endorsed sub-brand line beneath the master brand, so that each SKU borrows the credibility of the parent while remaining individually specifiable. Co-branded extensions, such as a joint “Re-Tire × partner” formulation, are reserved for Phase 4 and only under a formal joint-venture or licensing agreement. No consumer-facing brand is introduced before the upstream backbone is profitably established; introducing one earlier would dilute scarce marketing resources and contradict the upstream-supply thesis of the plan.
4.1.5  Brand Name, Visual Identity, and Tagline
Against the eight criteria of a strong brand name, unique, distinctive, registrable and protectable, positively connoted, short, suggestive, easy to say and recognise, memorable and extendable, and translatable, the name “Re-Tire” performs well: it is short, suggestive of both tire recycling and renewal, easy to pronounce across Arabic, French, and English, and registrable as set out in Section 4.5.6. The visual identity is engineering-clean: a slate-grey and forest-green palette, sans-serif typography, and a mark depicting a tire cross-section resolving into a granular mesh. It deliberately avoids the consumer-friendly, pastel tile aesthetics of the former tile-thesis competitors, signalling instead an industrial supplier. The brand promise is condensed into a tagline that, in the lean-planning sense, explains the brand in a few words: “Mesh you can specify. Origin you can prove.” The tagline maps directly onto the two core pain relievers, specification discipline and provable Lebanese origin, and is operationalised by the Certificate of Analysis and the GAFTA Certificate of Origin.
4.1.6  Brand Identity and Personality
Read through Kapferer’s brand-identity prism, the Re-Tire brand has a physique of clean industrial precision, a personality of competence and reliability, a relationship of dependable partnership, a culture of Lebanese circular-economy renewal, a reflection of a buyer who is rigorous and forward-looking, and a self-image of a procurement professional who has made a defensible, well-documented choice. On the brand-personality dimensions, the venture positions itself squarely on competence, reliable, hardworking, technical, secure, rather than on excitement or ruggedness. This is the correct personality for an industrial-feedstock brand: the buyer is not seeking novelty or self-expression but assurance, and a competence-led personality is what converts an unknown newcomer into a credible supplier.
Brand equity, the value the brand adds beyond the physical product, is built deliberately and, importantly, measured. For Re-Tire Lebanon the equity-building sequence is staged: brand awareness first, established through the promotion programme of Section 4.3; then a credible brand image, accumulated through consistent Certificate-of-Analysis performance and visible regulatory compliance; then favourable brand responses, evidenced by qualification trials converting to offtake contracts; and finally durable brand relationships, the multi-year agreements that are the venture’s ultimate commercial objective. Each stage is tracked: awareness through reach and qualified-enquiry counts, image through the tone of trade-press and customer feedback, responses through the funnel-conversion metrics of Section 4.5.5, and relationships through contract tenure and the customer-concentration trajectory. Treating brand equity as a measured asset rather than an intangible aspiration is consistent with the evidentiary discipline of the whole plan, and it gives a reviewer or an investor a concrete way to judge whether the marketing investment is compounding into a durable position.
4.1.7  Packaging and Branding Cost
Packaging is part of the product decision, not an afterthought. Re-Tire Lebanon ships in one-tonne flexible intermediate bulk containers, the industry-standard format for bulk crumb, printed with the SKU designation, the batch number, the mesh specification, and a quick-response code linking to the digital Certificate of Analysis. The packaging therefore performs three jobs at once: it protects and meters the product, it carries the brand into the customer’s receiving yard, and it makes traceability tangible. Branding incurs real creation cost, modest but explicit: trademark registration as detailed in Section 4.5.6, the design of the visual identity and the FIBC print, and a basic sales-collateral suite. These costs are carried in the Year 1 marketing budget rather than treated as free, in keeping with the plan’s discipline of costing every element.
4.1.8  Development and the R&D Commitment
A product is never finished, and the lean-planning toolbox treats the development pipeline, underwritten by a defined research-and-development budget, as part of the product offer. Re-Tire Lebanon's development path has three horizons. In Phase 1 the development effort is the qualification work itself: tuning mesh tolerances and screen settings to meet the anchor customer's recipe. In Phase 2 the venture develops asphalt-rubber binder grades to the ASTM D6114 specification, opening the rubberised-asphalt channel. In Phase 3 it evaluates cryogenic grinding to produce the fine fractions above 30 mesh that the ambient process cannot economically reach. A modest dedicated R&D line in the financial model funds this pipeline; presenting development as a budgeted commitment rather than an aspiration is what makes the venture's growth claims credible to a reviewer.
4.1.9  The Customer-Satisfaction Foundation
Underlying all five marketing components is a single organising idea the lean-planning toolbox places at the centre of the contemporary marketing plan: customer satisfaction, built on the triad of quality, delivery, and cost. A venture cannot lead on all three at once, and Re-Tire Lebanon's deliberate choice is to lead on quality and delivery while remaining strongly competitive on cost. Quality means high performance and reliability, the certificate-backed, batch-tested consistency that removes the procurement director's central fear. Delivery means quick response, the seven-day domestic and fourteen-day GAFTA service level that imports cannot match. Cost means outstanding value at the chosen price point, not the lowest price, but a fair price for genuinely high quality. The marketing plan that follows is, in effect, the systematic pursuit of this triad: the product and branding component builds quality, the place and selling components build delivery, and the price component secures value. Holding the triad explicitly in view keeps the five components aligned to one end, a satisfied industrial customer who renews and recommends, rather than optimised separately.
4.2  Price
Price is the only marketing-mix element that generates revenue rather than cost, and the lean-planning toolbox frames it through four questions: how the venture makes money, where it sits on the price-quality matrix, which pricing strategy it adopts, and how its price differs from competitors'. Each is addressed in turn, and the section closes with the pricing matrix, the pricing-decision factors, and the pricing discipline that holds the strategy together.
4.2.1  How the Venture Makes Money
Re-Tire Lebanon earns revenue from five streams, in descending order of Phase 1 weight: crumb sales across the three SKUs; RC-Steel by-product sales sized to cover monthly operating expenditure; tipping or gate fees of approximately USD 0.20 per tire from Year 2, once the collection network reaches critical mass; optional carbon-credit pre-sales from Phase 2; and Phase 4 co-branded royalties. The structural feature that defines the model is the steel cross-subsidy: because by-product revenue is engineered to absorb fixed operating cost, the crumb price does not have to carry overhead, which gives the venture unusual freedom to price the crumb lines competitively while remaining profitable. This is the pricing consequence of the unit-economics insight established in Chapter III.
4.2.2  Position on the Price-Quality Matrix
The price-quality matrix locates an offer in one of nine cells formed by crossing three price levels with three quality levels. Re-Tire Lebanon positions deliberately in the high-quality, medium-price cell, the high-value strategy. The venture delivers genuinely high quality: batch-tested, ASTM-classified, certificate-backed crumb that informal shredders cannot match and that equals or exceeds imported granulate. It does not, however, price at the premium (high-price) level, because its structurally low cost base and the steel cross-subsidy make a medium price profitable, and because a medium price accelerates the supplier-qualification decision that is the venture's principal commercial bottleneck. A high-value position, high quality at a fair price, is the cell most likely to convert a risk-averse industrial buyer, and it is consciously distinct from both the premium cell (which would slow qualification) and the economy cell (which the venture's quality discipline does not need to occupy).
