4.2.3  Pricing Strategy
From the menu of pricing strategies, premium, penetration, economy, skimming, psychological, bundle, dynamic, and others, Re-Tire Lebanon adopts a primary strategy of value-based pricing supported by a controlled penetration element. Pricing is value-based, in the sense of Nagle and Müller (2017): the price reflects the economic value the feedstock delivers to the buyer, avoided import cost, avoided lead-time risk, avoided certification friction, rather than a simple cost-plus mark-up. The penetration element is deliberate but bounded: during the three-to-six-month qualification of the anchor customer, the first trial volumes are priced at the lower edge of the band to lower the buyer's switching barrier, after which price moves to the value-based level. The venture explicitly rejects a skimming strategy, which would forfeit qualification speed, and a pure economy strategy, which would be incompatible with its quality position. Two structural mechanisms support the strategy: a volume discount of five to ten percent on annual commitments above 500 tonnes, which rewards the offtake contracts the model depends on, and a five-percent rush surcharge on sub-five-day deliveries, which prices the venture's lead-time advantage explicitly rather than giving it away.
4.2.4  The Pricing Matrix and Difference from Competitors
Pricing is the outcome of weighing internal factors against external ones. The internal factors that push Re-Tire's price down are its structurally low cost base, negative-cost feedstock, LBP-anchored labour, the solar-PV energy hedge, and the steel cross-subsidy that frees the crumb price from carrying overhead. The internal factor that sets a floor is the 30% cost of capital, which the price must ultimately reward. The external factors are market condition (a recovering but fragile Lebanese economy), the quality-price relationship the venture has chosen, competitor pricing (imports above, informal supply below), the brand (a new entrant that cannot yet command a premium), and the place advantage of domestic proximity. Table 4.3 sets out the resulting Phase 1 pricing matrix by SKU, with the external benchmark each price is set against. Prices rise with mesh fineness, reflecting both the additional grinding energy required and the higher-value applications the finer fractions serve.
