The venture's price differs from competitors' in a specific and defensible way. It is materially below imported granulate, whose landed cost in Lebanon is USD 450–700 per tonne, a Free-On-Board price of USD 350–500, ocean freight of USD 50–90, customs clearance and demurrage of USD 25–50, and inland trucking of USD 15–30. Re-Tire's mid-band price of roughly USD 400 per tonne therefore captures a 15–40% landed-cost advantage, before counting the further value of a one-week lead time and the elimination of FATF-related correspondent-banking friction (FATF, 2024). At the same time the venture prices above the informal shredders, whose coarse, uncertified output is not a true substitute for compounder-grade crumb. The price is thus positioned in a genuine gap: below imports on cost, above informal supply on quality, and profitable at that point because of the steel cross-subsidy. A dual-currency invoicing clause, USD-pegged with an optional Lebanese-pound equivalent at the Banque du Liban platform rate on the payment date, reconciles the venture's preference for hard-currency receipts with customer convenience.
4.2.5  Pricing Discipline and Contract Architecture
Pricing discipline is what distinguishes a mature B2B operation from an informal one, and it operates across four dimensions. The first is posted-price discipline: the venture maintains a published price list for the three crumb SKUs with quarterly review cycles and explicit off-cycle revision triggers, a movement of more than 10% in the London HMS-1 steel benchmark, more than 15% in the diesel benchmark, or more than 5% in the Lebanese-pound platform rate. The second is discount discipline: volume discounts follow a published schedule, any exception requires dual founder signature consistent with the governance protocol of Chapter I, and discount data is tracked centrally to detect drift toward price erosion. The third is contract architecture: a standardised master supply agreement governs volume floors and ceilings, quality tolerances and remediation, payment and currency terms, force-majeure provisions calibrated to the Lebanese context, and dispute resolution under Lebanese arbitration. The fourth is payment discipline: invoices issue on dispatch, terms are net 30 days, late-payment surcharges are explicitly contracted, and credit limits are managed against a documented customer credit-scoring framework. Together these four dimensions ensure that the value-based pricing strategy of Section 4.2.3 is actually realised in cash rather than eroded transaction by transaction.
4.3  Promotion Strategies
Promotion is the communication element of the marketing mix, in contemporary terms, the integrated marketing communication that builds brand equity. The promotion programme draws on the full integrated-communication toolkit, advertising, sales promotion, events and experiences, public relations and publicity, direct and interactive marketing, word-of-mouth marketing, and personal selling, but selects from it deliberately rather than using every instrument. The selection is governed by a single test: an industrial newcomer must build brand equity, and brand equity in this market is built from brand awareness, a credible brand image, favourable brand responses, and ultimately durable brand relationships. The lean-planning toolbox structures the work in three steps: setting communication objectives, designing the channel mix that pursues them, and measuring conversion along the customer path. The section follows that order and closes with the promotion budget, the digital toolkit, and the lower-cost promotional instruments suited to a capital-constrained venture.
4.3.1  Communication Objectives
Communication objectives fall into three families, informational, emotional, and behavioural, and Re-Tire Lebanon’s promotion programme is built against specific objectives in each. The informational objectives dominate, as is appropriate for an industrial newcomer: to explain what qualified crumb feedstock is, to build awareness of Re-Tire as a credible Lebanese supplier, to create exposure among a defined set of regional procurement managers, and to differentiate the venture’s certificate-backed offer from both informal and imported alternatives. The behavioural objectives are to reduce the risk-resistance of the procurement persona, to motivate a first qualification trial, and to build preference and contractual loyalty thereafter. The emotional objectives are the most modest, industrial buyers are not moved by sentiment, but not absent: the venture seeks to attach a quiet sense of confidence and national contribution to the brand, so that choosing Re-Tire feels like a sound and even a civic decision. Every promotional investment in the plan is justified by reference to one or more of these objectives.
4.3.2  Communication Objectives in Practice: A Worked Set
To make the communication objectives of Section 4.3.1 concrete, the venture defines, for Phase 1, a specific and prioritised set against which every promotional activity is judged. The first objective is to be known, to move from zero recognition to being a named option in the consideration set of the twenty target accounts within the first year. The second is to differentiate, to ensure that, wherever the brand is recognised, it is recognised specifically as the certificate-backed, Lebanese-origin supplier rather than as a generic recycler. The third is to build technical credibility, to establish, through datasheets, demonstration days, and trade-press explanation, that the venture’s quality discipline is real and verifiable. The fourth is to reduce purchase resistance, to lower, through reference cases and transparent specification, the procurement director’s fear of qualifying a new supplier. The fifth is to stimulate advocacy, to convert satisfied early customers into visible references. These five objectives are sequenced deliberately: the venture cannot pursue advocacy before it has built credibility, and cannot reduce resistance before it is known. The promotion budget of Section 4.3.5 is allocated in roughly this order of priority, and each budget line is justified by naming the objective it serves, the discipline that prevents marketing spend from drifting into activity without purpose.
4.3.3  The Five-A Customer Path
The Marketing 4.0 framework of Kotler, Kartajaya and Setiawan (2017) models the customer journey as five stages, aware, appeal, ask, act, and advocate. The path is useful here because it disciplines the promotion plan to ask, of any activity, which stage it is designed to move a buyer through. For Re-Tire Lebanon: the aware stage is served by LinkedIn reach and trade-media presence; the appeal stage by content that makes the certificate-backed, Lebanese-origin proposition attractive; the ask stage by founder-led conversations at industry events where a buyer’s questions can be answered directly; the act stage by the qualification trial and the offtake contract; and the advocate stage by the post-delivery reference and case-study programme. Two summary measures track the path: the Purchase Action Ratio, which measures how effectively awareness converts to purchase, and the Brand Advocacy Ratio, which measures how effectively awareness converts to spontaneous recommendation. In the closed, word-of-mouth-driven world of Lebanese industrial procurement, the Brand Advocacy Ratio is strategically as important as the purchase ratio, because a single credible reference customer materially shortens the next buyer’s qualification.
4.3.4  Promotion Channel Architecture
The promotion channel architecture has five layers, each mapped to a stage of the customer path. The first is organic and paid activity on LinkedIn, targeting industrial procurement managers in Lebanon, the United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia, and Egypt, with content on circular-economy credentials, Lebanese-origin advantages, and Certificate-of-Analysis discipline; this layer principally serves the aware and appeal stages. The second is in-person presence at Association of Lebanese Industrialists events and IDAL investor fora, where founder-led senior-relationship selling generates the highest-quality leads and serves the appeal and ask stages. The third is sponsorship and editorial presence at Berytech and UNDP demonstration days, which supplies grant-credibility validation. The fourth is trade-media presence in titles such as Tire & Rubber Recycling, MEED, and L’Orient-Le Jour Économie, serving aware and, through testimonial coverage, advocate. The fifth is direct founder-led selling to a defined top-twenty named-account list, the layer that does the decisive work at the act stage. In the language of contemporary digital media, the architecture deliberately combines owned media (the website and the venture’s own content), earned media (trade-press coverage and word of mouth), shared media (LinkedIn engagement), and a modest amount of paid media (targeted LinkedIn advertising).
4.3.5  Promotion Budget
The annual promotion budget is USD 35,000 in Year 1, rising to USD 50,000 in Year 2 and USD 60,000 in Year 3, allocated as shown in Table 4.4. The allocation reflects the customer-path logic: the LinkedIn line, which serves the high-volume aware and appeal stages, grows fastest as the platform’s regional industrial audience matures; the website line is front-loaded in Year 1 to support launch and then falls to a maintenance level; and conference sponsorship scales up in Year 2, once the venture has reference customers to cite in panel presentations and case studies, strengthening the ask and advocate stages.
