4.3.6  Conversion Diagnostics: Reading the Funnel Shape
The five-A path is also a diagnostic tool: the shape of the conversion funnel tells the venture where its marketing is failing. A weak conversion from aware to appeal signals low customer attraction, poor positioning or weak communication, and is addressed by repositioning or sharper messaging. A weak conversion from appeal to ask signals low curiosity, addressed through content and community marketing; conversely, an unusually high appeal-to-ask rate can signal that the brand message is unclear and is generating questions rather than confidence. A weak ask-to-act conversion signals low commitment despite interest, and points to a marketing-mix or channel flaw. A weak act-to-advocate conversion signals low affinity, customers are not delighted enough to recommend, and points to after-sales service or product performance. For Re-Tire Lebanon the funnel is expected to take the “goldfish” shape characteristic of a commoditised industrial input bought after lengthy, multi-stakeholder evaluation: a narrow ask stage and a demanding act stage. The strategic response that shape dictates is to invest in the curiosity and commitment stages, technical content, qualification trials, and reference cases, rather than in broad awareness spending, and to manage promotion so that the venture moves toward the ideal pattern in which awareness, purchase, and advocacy are closely aligned.
4.3.7  Sales Promotion and Guerrilla Tactics
Beyond the standing channel mix, two lower-cost promotional instruments suit a capital-constrained venture. Sales promotion, time-bound incentives, is used selectively: an introductory qualification-trial price for the first secondary buyers and a modest volume rebate at contract signing both serve to attract new customers, to encourage existing customers to buy more, and to bring forward a purchase decision, without becoming a permanent discount. Guerrilla tactics, creative, low-budget actions designed to generate word-of-mouth buzz, are appropriate given the venture’s limited resources: a worked demonstration of open-tire-burning harm versus recycled output at an industry day, or a visible plant-gate collection event with a partner municipality, can generate trade-press and social attention disproportionate to their cost. Both instruments are constrained by the brand’s competence personality: they must inform and impress, never trivialise the industrial proposition.
4.3.8  Digital Marketing and the Online Toolkit
Contemporary marketing is digital-first even in industrial B2B, and the lean-planning toolbox frames the digital layer through the four Cs, the online complement to the four Ps, and through the distinction between paid, owned, earned, and shared media. Re-Tire Lebanon’s digital toolkit is deliberately concentrated rather than spread thin. Owned media is a single professional website with search-engine optimisation around the specific terms a regional procurement manager would use, “crumb rubber supplier Lebanon,” “ASTM D5603 recycled rubber,” “GAFTA crumb feedstock”, together with downloadable technical datasheets and the digital Certificate-of-Analysis archive. Earned media is trade-press coverage and, above all, customer word of mouth, the most valuable channel in this market. Shared media is LinkedIn, the only social platform where industrial procurement audiences genuinely congregate; the venture maintains a company page and the founders maintain active professional profiles, because in B2B the personal credibility of a named engineer outperforms a corporate account. Paid media is a small, tightly targeted LinkedIn advertising budget aimed by job title, industry, and geography. The venture deliberately does not pursue consumer-oriented platforms, mass content production, or influencer marketing: these would consume scarce resources without reaching the procurement decision-maker. The digital strategy is judged not by follower counts but by lead quality, the number of qualified procurement enquiries it delivers into the funnel of Section 4.5.5.
4.4  Place
Place, distribution, concerns how the product reaches the customer. Because Re-Tire Lebanon sells a bulk industrial input to a small number of identified buyers, its place strategy is short and direct rather than multi-tiered, but the choice is deliberate and is tested below against the standard channel-choice factors.
4.4.1  The Distribution Channel
The venture operates a direct, zero-intermediary channel: product moves from the Keserwan-Matn plant to the customer’s dock with no wholesaler or distributor in between. Delivery is on Ex-Works or Free-Carrier Incoterms 2020 terms (ICC, 2019), with optional door-to-door logistics offered at cost-plus pricing for buyers without their own fleet. A direct channel is the right choice for three reasons: the customer set is small and identifiable, so an intermediary would add cost without adding reach; the product is technical and sold on specification, so the founder-led relationship cannot be delegated; and the venture needs the direct customer contact that generates the quality feedback and the references its growth depends on.
4.4.2  Factors Governing the Channel Choice
The lean-planning toolbox tests a channel against six factors, coverage, character, control, cost, capital requirement, and continuity. Re-Tire Lebanon’s direct channel performs well against each, as Table 4.5 sets out. The summary judgement is that a direct channel is not merely the cheapest option but the one that best fits the venture’s industrial-supplier character and its need for control over the quality and origin message.
Table 4.5  Channel-choice factors — assessment of the direct channel
Factor
Assessment for Re-Tire Lebanon’s Direct Channel
Coverage
Targeted, not mass: a small identified set of industrial buyers is reached directly and completely
Character
Fits the industrial-supplier brand; an intermediary would dilute the specification-led, founder-led identity
Control
Maximum: the venture controls the quality message, the CofA, the price, and the customer relationship
Cost
Low channel cost — no distributor margin; logistics offered at cost-plus rather than carried as overhead
Capital requirement
Minimal incremental capital; no distributor network or intermediary inventory to finance
Continuity
Strong: multi-year offtake contracts and direct relationships give the channel longevity and low churn
4.4.3  Site, Inbound Logistics, and Export Routing
Place also encompasses the physical siting of the operation. The venture operates from a single industrial site in Keserwan or peripheral Matn, with site selection favouring an Investment Development Authority of Lebanon Investment Project by Zone Class B classification for the higher tax-incentive stack available under Law 360/2001. Inbound logistics for waste-tire feedstock operate within a 25-to-40-kilometre radius, capturing an estimated 40 to 60 tire-shop nodes across Keserwan and Matn; the reverse-logistics design follows the closed-loop supply-chain principles of Guide and Van Wassenhove (2009) and the practical framework of Rogers and Tibben-Lembke (1999), and is developed operationally in Chapter V. For outbound export, Beirut Port serves Gulf Cooperation Council and Egypt shipments, while Tripoli Port and its Special Economic Zone are reserved for evaluation in Year 2 should the export share exceed half of total volume. The service-level commitment that anchors the place advantage is delivery within seven calendar days for Lebanese customers and within fourteen days for GAFTA destinations, a standard that imported granulate, at six-to-ten-week lead times, structurally cannot meet.
4.4.4  Channel Control and Customer-Relationship Management
Because the channel is direct, the venture carries the full responsibility for the customer relationship rather than delegating it to an intermediary, and this is treated as an asset, not a burden. Every customer interaction, from first enquiry to post-delivery follow-up, is captured in a customer-relationship-management system that records account health, product mix, quality-rejection history, payment behaviour, and renewal dates. The system does two jobs. Operationally, it ensures that a three-person founder team does not lose track of a commitment or a renewal across a growing account base. Strategically, it converts the direct channel into a structured feedback loop: the quality complaints, the mesh-mix shifts, and the lead-time pressures that surface in the CRM are the raw material for the product development of Section 4.1.8 and the operational adjustments of Chapter V. A direct channel without disciplined customer-relationship management would simply be an unmanaged set of contacts; with it, the channel becomes the venture’s primary instrument of learning.
4.4.5  The Customer Experience at the Point of Delivery
Even an industrial venture with no retail storefront creates a customer experience, and that experience is part of the place decision. For Re-Tire Lebanon the equivalent of a retailer’s store atmosphere is the experience a buyer has at the three points of contact with the operation: the plant gate, the delivery, and the documentation. The plant itself is kept visibly clean, orderly, and safety-compliant, because a procurement director who visits to qualify a supplier reads the state of the yard as evidence of the discipline of the process, a tidy, well-signed facility is itself a sales argument. The delivery experience is engineered to be predictable: palletised one-tonne containers, clear labelling, an accurate advance shipping notice, and a delivery window that is met. The documentation experience, the Certificate of Analysis, the GAFTA Certificate of Origin, the invoice, is designed to be clean, complete, and easy to file. Each of these contact points is low-cost to do well and disproportionately influential, because in a market where buyers cannot easily verify quality in advance, the professionalism of the experience stands in for the reputation the venture has not yet built.
4.4.6  Place and the Lebanese-Origin Advantage
The place strategy is, finally, inseparable from the venture’s core competitive claim. Being physically present in Lebanon is not a neutral fact of incorporation but the source of three advantages that no importer can replicate: the seven-day lead time, the elimination of the FATF-related correspondent-banking friction that burdens every cross-border payment, and the GAFTA Certificate of Origin that makes the product eligible for duty-free re-export across the Greater Arab Free Trade Area. Place, in other words, is where the marketing plan and the strategic thesis of the whole business plan meet: the decision to operate upstream and inside Lebanon, taken in Chapter I and validated in Chapter II, expresses itself in the marketing mix precisely as a distribution advantage. A reviewer should read Section 4.4 not as logistics housekeeping but as the marketing-mix component that monetises the venture’s location.
4.5  Selling Strategies
The fifth marketing-mix component is the selling strategy, the structure of the sales force, the sales expectations and budget, the account-management framework, and the service and warranty commitments that surround the sale. For a B2B feedstock venture the sales force is the heartbeat of the commercial model, and its design is set out below.
4.5.1  Sales-Force Structure
Re-Tire Lebanon uses a direct sales force, the three founders, rather than independent representatives, for the same reasons the distribution channel is direct: the sale is technical, relationship-led, and central to the venture’s feedback loop. The choice between a direct force and external reps is a deliberate one. External representatives would offer faster reach and a variable rather than fixed cost, but they would interpose a layer between the venture and the buyer precisely where the technical conversation and the quality message matter most, and they could not credibly carry the founder-level relationship the anchor account requires. A direct force is therefore correct for Phase 1, accepting that it caps the number of accounts the venture can pursue at once, which is itself consistent with the single-segment focus of Chapter II.
Accounts are allocated by founder competence. Tony Rayes owns the anchor compounder relationship and broader business development; Paul Tabet owns asphalt and operations-linked accounts; and Michael Mrad owns technical pilots and joint product-development engagements. As volume grows, the planned evolution, detailed in the organisation chart of Chapter VI, is to add a dedicated commercial hire once the secondary-buyer base justifies it, and a technical-sales support role once co-formulation pilots multiply, so that founders progressively move from doing the selling to managing it. This planned growth of the sales structure, rather than an assumption that three founders can sell indefinitely, is what makes the revenue ramp of the financial model credible.
4.5.2  Sales Expectations, Budget, and Margins
Sales expectations are expressed as proposal-to-contract latency and conversion targets rather than as a single revenue figure, because the qualification-driven nature of the market makes timing the critical variable. Proposal-to-contract latency is targeted at 90 days for Tier-1 anchor-class accounts, reflecting the realistic compounder-qualification cycle, and 45 days for Tier-2 accounts, whose qualification requirements are lighter. The sales budget is the founder-time cost plus the customer-relationship-management and collateral lines already carried within the promotion budget of Section 4.3.5; the venture does not operate an intermediary tier, so no distributor margin is given away, a structural advantage of the direct model. Volume-based discounts of five to ten percent on commitments above 500 tonnes are the only routine margin concession, and they are pre-published rather than negotiated case by case.
The margin logic of the selling strategy deserves to be stated plainly, because it is what makes the model financeable. In a conventional distribution model a manufacturer surrenders a margin layer, commonly 15 to 30 percent, to wholesalers and representatives. Re-Tire Lebanon’s direct, founder-led model retains that entire layer, which is one of the three structural margin advantages of the venture, alongside the negative-cost feedstock and the steel cross-subsidy. The selling strategy is therefore not only a route to revenue but a contributor to the contribution margin itself: every account the founders close directly is an account on which no intermediary margin is lost. The trade-off is the founder-time ceiling discussed in Section 4.5.1, which is precisely why the account-tiering of Section 4.5.3 exists, to ration that scarce founder time toward the accounts where the retained margin is largest. The sales expectations, the discount schedule, and the account tiers are thus a single coherent system, and the financial model of Chapter VIII inherits all three as explicit inputs rather than as assumptions.
4.5.3  The B2B Account-Management Framework
Because a three-person commercial team cannot give every customer equal attention, accounts are sorted into the four tiers defined in Chapter II and given differentiated coverage, as set out in Table 4.6. The framework is the operational core of the selling strategy: it concentrates founder time on the relationships that carry the most revenue and the most strategic weight, while still serving smaller buyers economically.
