Each managed account carries a standard account plan: an annual volume target by SKU, a mesh-mix plan reflecting the customer’s downstream portfolio, a quality-control rejection budget against which performance is measured, a joint-pilot pipeline, and a renewal-risk register flagging contract dates and known competitive threats. Account-level key performance indicators include the customer-concentration ratio, with a target of no more than 40% anchor share by the end of Year 2, the diversification discipline carried into Chapter IX, a Certificate-of-Analysis acceptance rate at or above 98%, payment days-sales-outstanding at or below 45 days, and an account-level satisfaction score.
4.5.4  Customer Personas
Effective selling requires the sales team to understand not only the segment but the individual buyer. Three personas are defined for the Phase 1 acquisition motion. The first is the compounder procurement director: typically a chemical or civil engineer with 15 to 25 years of experience, evaluated internally on cost per tonne of compound, batch-to-batch variance, and supply continuity, and whose dominant fear is that a new supplier’s quality variance will halt a production line. The selling approach for this persona must therefore lead with quality-discipline credibility, the Certificate of Analysis, ISO readiness, equipment specification, before any price conversation. The second is the asphalt project manager: a civil engineer operating inside a rigid Council for Development and Reconstruction tender framework, reachable only when tender specifications permit rubberised-asphalt content, which means the selling effort must include patient advocacy at the specification-writing layer rather than direct pursuit of the project manager alone. The third is the sports-surfacing installer: typically an owner-operator who buys personally and whose first criterion is local availability, small lots within 48 hours, so the selling approach leads with the lead-time service-level commitment. Defining personas at this resolution is what turns the segmentation of Chapter II into usable sales-team and content guidance.
4.5.5  Service, Warranty, and Conversion Discipline
The selling strategy is completed by the service and warranty commitments that follow the sale and by the conversion discipline that governs the funnel. Service and warranty matter disproportionately in industrial selling because they are what convert a first transaction into a multi-year relationship. Every shipment carries a Certificate of Analysis, and the master supply agreement specifies a defined remediation procedure, replacement or credit, for any batch that fails the contracted tolerances; this remediation clause functions as the venture’s product warranty, and naming it explicitly in the contract is itself a selling argument to a risk-averse buyer who has been burned by uncertified supply before. Beyond the warranty, the venture commits to a defined response standard for any quality query, acknowledgement within one working day and a resolution plan within three, because in this market the speed and seriousness of the after-sales response is what builds the affinity that turns a customer into an advocate. After-sales service is therefore not a cost centre tacked onto the sale but the final, decisive component of the marketing mix: it is where the act stage of the customer path becomes the advocate stage.
On conversion discipline: the venture tracks movement along the five-A path with explicit targets, summarised in Table 4.7. The Ask-to-Act target is set higher for Tier-1 accounts, because a compounder that has chosen to engage seriously converts at a high rate despite the long qualification, and lower for Tier-2 accounts, where competition is more intense. The Advocate target is set high for both tiers because, in the small Lebanese industrial community, a satisfied reference customer is the single most powerful selling instrument the venture has.
