4.5.6  Brand Registration and Protection
The selling strategy depends on a brand that is legally protected. Two registration steps are taken. First, the master brand “Re-Tire Lebanon” is registered as a national trademark in Lebanon under Resolution 2385/1924, in Nice Classification Class 17 (rubber and semi-finished plastics) and Class 40 (treatment of materials and recycling services), for a ten-year renewable term, at approximately USD 700–1,200 per class through the Intellectual Property Protection Office of the Ministry of Economy and Trade. Second, because Lebanon is not a party to the Madrid Protocol, protection in GAFTA export markets is pursued through separate national filings in each target country rather than through a single international application; the cost implications of this are addressed in Chapter VII. Registration is treated as a selling asset, not merely a legal formality: a registered, protected brand is part of the assurance the venture offers a buyer entering a multi-year relationship.
4.5.7  Marketing Risks and Mitigations
An honest marketing plan names the ways it could fail. Four marketing risks are material. The first is a qualification-cycle risk: the three-to-six-month compounder-qualification process could extend, delaying revenue; the mitigation is the penetration-priced trial of Section 4.2.3, which lowers the buyer’s barrier to starting the cycle, and the parallel seeding of Tier-2 accounts so that revenue does not depend on a single qualification completing on schedule. The second is a channel-concentration risk: with promotion concentrated on LinkedIn and a small number of trade events, a decline in the effectiveness of either would weaken the funnel; the mitigation is the deliberately multi-layered channel architecture of Section 4.3.4 and the primacy of founder-led direct selling, which does not depend on any media platform. The third is a price-perception risk: a medium price for a new and unknown supplier can be misread as a signal of medium quality, the “false-economy” misreading; the mitigation is to lead every conversation with quality evidence before price, exactly as the persona analysis of Section 4.5.4 prescribes. The fourth is a reference-dependency risk: the advocacy strategy relies on early customers becoming visible references, and a single dissatisfied early customer in a small community is disproportionately damaging; the mitigation is the after-sales service standard of Section 4.5.5 and the deliberate over-servicing of the first accounts. Naming these risks and pairing each with a mitigation already built into the plan is what distinguishes a marketing plan from a marketing wish.
4.5.8  Marketing Plan Synthesis and Key Performance Indicators
The five components of the contemporary marketing plan are not independent; they cohere around a single proposition. The product is a specification-disciplined, traceable feedstock; the price places that product in the high-value cell, below imports and above informal supply; the promotion communicates specification and origin through a customer-path-disciplined channel mix; the place delivers it directly and fast; and the selling strategy manages the qualification-driven relationship that the industrial sale requires. Each component reinforces the others: the direct channel makes the value-based price defensible, the quality discipline makes the promotion claims credible, and the account-management framework makes the lead-time promise deliverable. The plan’s success is measured against a small set of marketing key performance indicators, summarised in Table 4.8, each tied to a component and each carried into the financial model of Chapter VIII and the risk register of Chapter IX.
