≤ 90 days

These indicators make the marketing plan auditable rather than rhetorical: each is a number a reviewer or an investor can ask the venture to report against, and together they convert the five marketing components into a measurable management system.
This chapter has translated the v2.0 canvas into an executable marketing plan across all five lean-planning components. Chapter V converts the plan into the industrial process that must deliver it, the production diagram, the facilities and equipment, the suppliers and partners, and the operating schedule, so that the lead-time, quality, and capacity commitments made to the market here are matched by the operations that fulfill them.
Chapter V: Operations Management
Operations Management translates the refined Business Model Canvas of Chapter III and the marketing plan of Chapter IV into an executable industrial process. The chapter follows Professor Antoine Elhage’s prescribed structure, Production Diagram, Facilities and Equipment, Suppliers and Partners, Schedule, and adds three operational subsections (supply-chain risk, energy strategy, and quality management) that are required by the upstream-feedstock pivot. Every operational decision is traceable either to a Chapter II market finding (feedstock density, customer concentration, competitive threat) or to a Chapter IV marketing commitment (product specification, quality discipline, service promise).
5.1  Production Diagram: The Five-Machine Line
Re-Tire Lebanon’s production process follows the ambient-grinding pathway for mechanical tire recycling, which is the most widely deployed technology globally and the most economically appropriate for a startup-scale operation. The process flows through six sequential stages, each with defined inputs, outputs, throughput targets, and quality-control checkpoints. The five-machine equipment configuration recommended by the anonymised compounder during the primary-source field interview is the operational spine of the process: one debeaders, one shear shredder serving as a primary chopper, one granulator (Cracker mill) performing the secondary size-reduction step, and one separation-and-screening line.
Table 5.1: Production Process Stages
Stage
Process
Input → Output
Quality Control
1. Receiving & Sorting
Waste tires collected from partner garages (tire shops, truck fleets operators) across Keserwan-Matn via hub-and-spoke logistics; sorted by type and condition
Whole waste tires → sorted inventory
Visual inspection for severe damage; rejected tires flagged for TDF offtake
2. Debeading
 Debeader extract steel-bead wire from tire sidewalls
Whole tires → debeaded tires + bead wire
Steel-bead-wire purity check; throughput monitoring
3. Primary Shredding
Shear shredder reduces debeaded tires to chips of approximately 50 mm
Debeaded tires → chips ≈50 mm
Throughput monitoring; chip-size sampling per shift
4. Granulation
Chips reduced to crumb of 30mm; rare-earth magnetic separation extracts steel; air classifier removes textile fibre
Chips → crumb 30 mm + steel + fibre
Mesh-size screening; magnetic purity test
5. Screening & Grading
Crumb screened into 20- and 30-mesh fractions per ASTM D5644
Crumb → graded RC-20/30
Particle-size distribution per ASTM D5644 per batch; sample retention
6. Bagging & Dispatch
FIBC bagging with batch-tagged CofA; outbound dispatch
Graded crumb → palletised inventory + dispatch
100 % weight check; CofA issuance per ASTM D5603

Material balance per 52 kg truck tire yields approximately 35-40 kg of crumb (68 %), 12 kg of steel (23%), 1-2kg of fibre (3 %), and 1 kg of process loss and fines (2% %). Energy intensity for crumb-rubber production is approximately 3,849 megajoules per tonne (≈1.07 kWh per kg of crumb produced) under conventional grid power, per the comprehensive life-cycle assessment of Tushar, Santos, Zhang, Bhuiyan and Giustozzi (2022) of RMIT University. This figure is the technical anchor for the energy strategy of Section 5.6.
Throughput targets for Phase 2 steady-state operations are approximately 800 kilograms of crumb rubber per hour at the granulation stage and approximately 5 tonnes per day on a single-shift basis. The bottleneck under the initial equipment configuration is the shear shredder rather than the granulator. This ordering is deliberate: crumb is storable as work-in-progress, whereas feedstock tires consume more storage volume per tonne, so having excess granulation capacity downstream of the shredder bottleneck is preferable to the reverse.
5.2  Facilities and Equipment
The production facility requires approximately 2,000 to 2,500 square metres of industrial space, ideally located in the Zouk Mosbeh to Dbayeh industrial corridor for proximity to both feedstock sources in Keserwan-Matn and to the anchor customer’s Mount Lebanon pilot facility. Site-selection criteria include ceiling clearance of at least 5.5 metres but ideally 7 meters for the granulator and dust-collection ducting, three-phase electrical supply for approximately 250 to 350 kilowatts of peak demand, flat vehicle access for tire-delivery trucks and finished-goods dispatch, and sufficient outdoor covered area for NFPA-compliant tire storage.
5.2.1  Fire-Safety and Tire-Storage Compliance
Tire storage is governed by specific fire-safety requirements because tire piles are high-energy fuel loads with serious combustion-risk implications. The reference framework is the National Fire Protection Association Standard 1, 2018 edition, Chapter 33, “Outside Storage of Tires” (NFPA, 2018), which sets the following dimensional limits for new outdoor tire-storage piles: maximum 10 ft (3 m) height, 50 ft (15 m) width, 250 ft (76 m) length, and 50 ft (15 m) minimum separation from perimeter fencing. Individual-pile separation distances are governed by Table 33.1.3 of the standard. Smoking, open flames, welding and cutting are prohibited within the tire-storage area, and the operator must develop and submit an emergency-response plan to the Authority Having Jurisdiction.
Indoor tire storage is regulated separately. Under the International Fire Code (Chapter 32, 2021 edition) and NFPA Standard 13, rubber tires are designated a high-hazard commodity for which the Authority Having Jurisdiction may reduce the high-piled-combustible-storage threshold from 12 ft to 6 ft (1.8 m) of stacking height, triggering sprinkler-system and smoke-control requirements. Re-Tire Lebanon’s facility design therefore defaults to outdoor covered storage configured to Chapter 33 limits, with a maximum on-site inventory of approximately 30 to 45 days of production feedstock (200 to 400 tonnes) to balance fire-risk minimisation against supply-chain buffer. Mosquito-breeding prevention, a specific environmental-health requirement given that waste tires harbour Aedes mosquito larvae at high densities, requires covered storage or a daily-drainage protocol for any stockpiled tires that could retain standing water; covered storage is the specified default.
