Each phase transitions to the next only when defined gating milestones are met. Phase 1 to Phase 2 requires twelve consecutive months of compounder-qualified output and three months of positive operating cash flow. Phase 2 to Phase 3 requires successful execution of at least one CDR asphalt contract. Phase 3 to Phase 4 requires validated downstream demand at branded-product price points. The gating discipline prevents the common failure mode of premature scale-up.
5.5  Supply-Chain Risk
Key supply-chain risks include equipment spare-parts lead time (Beirut Port to plant delivery of 8 to 12 weeks for complex parts), feedstock interruption from political events affecting the country and logistics-fuel volatility. Mitigations include two complete sets of consumables purchased at the time of original equipment commissioning, consignment-stocking arrangements with the primary European supplier, a 30-to-60-day feedstock stockpile within NFPA Chapter 33 limits, dual-municipality contracts to diversify feedstock supply, and a dollarised-diesel pass-through clause in customer contracts that transfers fuel-cost risk to buyers.
5.6  Energy Strategy with Solar Hedge
Électricité du Liban grid commercial tariff is USD 0.247 per kilowatt-hour. Private-generator blended cost is USD 0.32 to 0.38 per kilowatt-hour as of mid-2025. At a verified energy intensity of approximately 1.07 kWh per kilogram of crumb produced (Tushar et al., 2022), Re-Tire Lebanon’s installed load is approximately 250 to 350 kilowatts peak with 1.0 to 1.5 gigawatt-hours per year energy consumption at full single-shift utilisation. A 100 to 150 kWp rooftop solar photovoltaic system at USD 800 to 1,200 per kWp turnkey, per the Lebanese Centre for Energy Conservation 2023 Solar PV Status Report (LCEC, 2025), which documents turnkey costs falling from USD 7,186 per kWp in 2011 to USD 1,003 per kWp in 2023, an 86 % decline, generates 150 to 225 MWh per year. This displaces USD 50,000 to 80,000 per year of generator-blended-cost electricity, with a simple payback of 1.8 to 2.5 years. The solar installation is the highest-internal-rate-of-return capital-expenditure tranche of the entire project.
5.7  Quality Management System Architecture
The quality-management-system architecture is the operational backbone that converts the venture’s Certificate of Analysis discipline (Chapter IV, Section 4.1) into a credible commercial promise. Re-Tire Lebanon targets ISO 9001 quality-management-system certification by end-Year 2 and ISO 14001 environmental-management-system certification by end-Year 3, sequenced so that the operational discipline of ISO 9001 is established before the more demanding documentation requirements of ISO 14001 are layered on top (ISO, 2015a; ISO, 2015b).
5.7.1  Mesh-Grade Quality Control
Mesh-grade quality control is performed at each batch, typically defined as a one-tonne FIBC, through stratified random sampling. Three samples per batch are extracted at the bagging station; particle-size distribution is determined using a Ro-Tap sieve-shaker per ASTM Standard D5644 (ASTM International, 2023b) against the SKU specifications classified per ASTM Standard D5603 (ASTM International, 2023a); and the results are recorded in the batch-tracking database. Out-of-specification batches are flagged for rework or downgrade to the coarser SKU, the fall-through hierarchy being RC-30 → RC-20 → scrap-tire offtake. Sample retention is twelve months from production, allowing post-shipment quality investigation in the event of customer dispute.
5.7.2  Residual-Contamination Quality Control
Residual-contamination quality control covers metal content, fibre content, and moisture content, the three contamination categories most likely to disrupt downstream compounder processes. Metal-content testing uses neodymium-magnet pull-down on pre-weighed samples with an acceptance ceiling of 0.1 %. Fibre-content testing uses air-classifier separation on pre-weighed samples with an acceptance ceiling of 0.5 %. Moisture-content testing uses oven-drying loss-on-mass methodology with an acceptance ceiling of 0.75 %. The three results, together with the mesh-grade particle-size distribution, are printed on the Certificate of Analysis that accompanies every shipment.
5.8  Reverse-Logistics Operating Model
Reverse logistics, the inbound flow of waste-tire feedstock from generation points to the processing facility, is the operational dimension most likely to differentiate Re-Tire Lebanon from competitors at the unit-economics level, because feedstock logistics costs are structurally a large fraction of cash operating expenditure. The operating model draws on Rogers and Tibben-Lembke (1999), De Brito and Dekker (2004), Guide and Van Wassenhove (2009), and the network-design model of Fleischmann, Krikke, Dekker and Flapper (2000).
5.8.1  Network Design
The network follows a hub-and-spoke topology with the Re-Tire processing facility as the hub and approximately 60 tire-shop nodes across Keserwan and Matn as spokes. The choice over a point-to-point alternative is driven by three considerations: tire-shop nodes individually generate low daily volumes (typically 50 to 200 tires per day) that do not justify dedicated trip frequencies; intermediate aggregation is impractical because waste tires are voluminous relative to mass, making intermediate stockpiles space-inefficient; and the Phase 1 capital constraint precludes deploying intermediate transfer stations.
5.8.2  Supplier-Tier Architecture
Supplier-tier architecture distinguishes Tier-1 anchor suppliers (large fleet operators, government vehicle pools) generating ≥500 kg per pickup at a contracted minimum cadence; Tier-2 strategic suppliers (large independent tire shops and dealer networks) generating 200–500 kg per pickup; and Tier-3 transactional suppliers (small independent tire shops) served on a route-optimised rather than fixed-frequency basis. Each tier has a defined service-level contract specifying pickup cadence, payment or no-fee terms, and quality-acceptance criteria for rejected tires.
5.8.3  Reverse-Flow Information System
The reverse-flow information system tracks each tire from pickup to processing through a tablet-based field-data-entry application used by the truck driver and a back-office consolidation database. Data elements per pickup include source tire-shop identifier, pickup date and time, vehicle registration, weight at pickup (estimated by tire count), and rejection-flag for non-conforming tires. The system enables three operational outputs: supplier-payment reconciliation for any tipping-fee suppliers, feedstock-quality variance analysis by source, and route-optimisation analytics for the inbound transport network.
5.9  Continuous Improvement and Operational Excellence
Continuous improvement at Re-Tire Lebanon’s startup scale is structured around two formal practices and one cultural principle. The first formal practice is a weekly cross-functional operations review covering plant operations, customer feedback, and supplier performance through a standard agenda that ensures continuity across personnel rotation. The second formal practice is a quarterly Plan-Do-Check-Act improvement cycle in which one or two specific operational metrics are selected for focused improvement with target outcomes, intervention design, measurement protocol and post-intervention review. The cultural principle is shop-floor empowerment: any operator may halt production for a quality concern without prior approval and without consequence, modelled on the Toyota Production System andon principle. Founder communication discipline reinforces the principle: when an operator halts production, the founder response is appreciation rather than interrogation, regardless of whether the halt was strictly necessary.
Chapter VI translates this operational architecture into the human-resource framework required to staff and develop the team, with explicit reference to Hambrick and Mason’s (1984) upper-echelons perspective and to the lean-startup staffing logic of Ries (2011).

Chapter VI: Human Resource Management
Human Resource Management sets out the venture’s approach to building and developing the team that will execute the business plan. The chapter addresses the roles and responsibilities of Key Managers, Additional Employees, Organisation Chart and Company Culture, and extends the prescribed structure with subsections on Performance Management, Succession Planning, Compensation Philosophy, and Diversity and Inclusion in the Lebanese confessional context. The chapter is grounded in the upper-echelons perspective of Hambrick and Mason (1984), which establishes that the composition, capabilities and cognitive diversity of a venture’s top-management team materially affect strategic outcomes, and in the lean-startup staffing logic of Ries (2011), which prescribes deliberately lean teams with cross-functional responsibilities in the early stages before functional specialisation is justified by revenue.
6.1  Key Managers
The three founders constitute the executive team of Re-Tire Lebanon. Their functional responsibilities are summarised in Chapter I, Section 1.1.1, and elaborated here at the level of detail required for the Human Resource Management chapter.
6.1.1  Michael Mrad: Chief Technology and Innovation Officer
Michael Mrad oversees production technology, quality control, the ISO 9001 quality-management and ISO 14001 environmental-management system implementations, and Phase 3 cryogenic-grinding feasibility exploration. He is responsible for ensuring technical feasibility at each stage of the production process and for driving continuous process improvement per Section 5.9. His cross-functional responsibilities include the information-systems architecture (the ERP platform, the CRM system, and the quality-tracking database) and the evidence base for market research and customer analytics. He is the founder most directly engaged with equipment suppliers, certification auditors, and technical service providers.
6.1.2  Paul Tabet: Chief Operating Officer
Paul Tabet manages supply-chain operations, collection logistics, production scheduling, facility management, procurement, and the financial-planning function detailed in Chapter VIII. He is responsible for operational efficiency and for the strategic coherence of the business plan over time. His cross-functional responsibilities include supplier-relationship management across both the upstream feedstock tier and the imported-inputs tier, as well as the working-capital management discipline that Lebanon’s banking-crisis context makes a permanent priority. He is the founder most directly engaged with municipalities, the Ministry of Environment, and the donor-incubator ecosystem comprising Berytech, the UNDP Lebanon Green Investment Facility, the EU 2CIRCULAR programme, and the European Neighbourhood Instrument Cross-Border Cooperation Mediterranean grants.
6.1.3  Tony Rayes: Chief Commercial Officer
Tony Rayes leads client acquisition, partnership development, marketing execution, customer-relationship management, and revenue generation. He is responsible for commercial traction in Phase 1 (the 10-to-20 anchor-and-strategic accounts framework of Chapter IV, Section 4.8) and for the referral-driven and CDR-driven expansion of Phase 2 and Phase 3. His cross-functional responsibilities include brand stewardship, the B2B account-management framework, and export-market development through the GAFTA channel from Phase 3 onward.
6.2  Additional Employees
Initial staffing beyond the founders is deliberately lean, reflecting both the lean-startup philosophy of Ries (2011) and the practical capital constraints of a Lebanese early-stage venture. Year 1 headcount target is nine full-time equivalents inclusive of the three founders, comprising: one plant manager at USD 1,500 per month, one maintenance technician at USD 1,000 per month, two production operators at USD 700 per month each, one logistics and yard operator at USD 600 per month, and one administrative-and-finance assistant at USD 900 per month. The total Year 1 personnel envelope includes NSSF employer contributions of 17 % composite (11 % sickness and maternity plus 6 % family allowances) plus end-of-service indemnity at 8.5 % uncapped, for a combined 25.5 % statutory employer load (L’Orient Today, 2020; PwC Worldwide Tax Summaries, 2025). Total personnel cost in Year 1 is approximately USD 163,000.
