All Year 1 employee wages are above the Decree 699/2025 minimum wage of LBP 28 million per month (approximately USD 313 at the unified market rate), with the production-operator role positioned at approximately 2.2× minimum wage, reflecting the venture’s compensation philosophy articulated in Section 6.7.
6.3  Organisation Chart
The organisational structure is deliberately flat and organic in Phase 1 and Phase 2, reflecting both the lean-startup philosophy and the small initial team size. The three co-founders report to each other as equals on strategic decisions, with operational decision-making distributed by domain expertise. Production staff report to Michael Mrad in the technical-and-innovation domain. Collection, logistics and procurement staff report to Paul Tabet in the operations-and-strategy domain. Sales, marketing and customer-service staff report to Tony Rayes in the commercial-and-business-development domain. Cross-functional teams are formed for specific projects: a new customer installation, for example, typically involves production staff under Michael’s direction, logistics coordination under Paul’s direction, and customer-relationship management under Tony’s direction, operating as a coherent project team for the duration of the engagement.
As the organisation grows through Phase 3, functional departments will crystallise around three domains, operations, commercial, and technical, with the co-founders transitioning from player-coaches to team leaders as span-of-control increases. The target Year-3 structure maintains the cross-functional, low-formalisation character of the founding phase even as formal reporting lines are introduced.
6.4  Company Culture
Drawing on the upper-echelons proposition of Hambrick and Mason (1984), the founder team’s values directly shape culture. Six principles anchor the culture, framed as behaviours rather than aspirations so that they are testable against daily decisions and hiring choices.
First, transparency. Operating and financial data is shared with the full team on a weekly basis through a Friday-morning structured meeting that reviews production output, quality variances, customer activity, cash position, and any operational issues. Second, safety first. NFPA-aligned drills are held monthly; a zero-tolerance smoking policy is enforced on site per NFPA Chapter 33 requirements; any safety incident triggers an immediate halt-and-investigate response. Third, anti-corruption. The no-bribe policy is modelled explicitly on the Cedar Environmental precedent (Hsieh & Abdel Aal, 2021) and is treated as a non-negotiable strategic asset rather than a normative aspiration. Fourth, circular pride. Every employee receives quarterly reporting on tonnes of tires diverted, CO₂-equivalent avoided, and customer applications served, so that the operational meaning of the venture’s circular-economy mission is concrete rather than abstract. Fifth, low formalisation. Written policies are kept minimal and introduced only when a recurring decision pattern justifies codification. Sixth, employee empowerment. Cross-trained employees who can operate multiple stations and make routine decisions without escalation are explicitly developed, because this structure is operationally resilient and developmentally engaging.
6.5  Performance Management
Performance management combines weekly operational reviews, monthly one-on-one development conversations, and quarterly written feedback. The combined cadence delivers the substance of performance management without the form overhead that a small venture cannot support. The training and skill-development budget allocates approximately USD 1,500 to 3,000 per employee per year, prioritising technical skills (operator cross-training, equipment maintenance, quality-testing protocols), commercial skills (customer engagement, specification-language familiarity, presentation capability), and leadership skills for the emerging middle layer comprising the production supervisor and the sales representative roles.
The performance-management framework operates against three tiers of Key Performance Indicators. Plant-operations indicators track Overall Equipment Effectiveness with a target of ≥65 % on single-shift operations, throughput tonnes per labour hour, and safety incidents with a zero target. Commercial indicators track customer-concentration ratio per Chapter II, CofA acceptance rate of ≥98 %, payment days-sales-outstanding ≤45 days, and account Net Promoter Score. Environmental and compliance indicators track tonnes of tires diverted from open dumping or burning, CO₂-equivalent avoided, and the pass rate on NFPA and Environmental Compliance Certificate audits. Annual review cycles are linked to merit increases tied to KPI achievement, with a bonus pool of 5 % of net profit in any year in which net profit is positive.
6.6  Succession Planning
The three-founder structure creates specific key-person risk that must be managed deliberately. The unplanned departure of any founder, whether through voluntary exit, health event, or other cause, would materially disrupt the venture, particularly in Phase 1 when each founder holds unique operational knowledge. The risk gradually moderates through Phase 2 and Phase 3 as institutional knowledge is transferred to the expanded team.
Mitigation mechanisms operate across three layers. First, cross-functional familiarity: each founder maintains working familiarity with the other two domains, so that an unplanned departure is a crisis but not an extinction event. Second, documented processes: as the ISO 9001 and ISO 14001 certification work proceeds in Phase 2, the documented-process output functions as institutional knowledge capture that is robust to individual departures. Third, equity vesting: the founder-equity structure uses a four-year vesting schedule with a one-year cliff, which aligns long-term commitment with long-term ownership. The Phase 2 and Phase 3 organisational expansion explicitly creates the middle layer, production supervisor, quality-control technician, sales representative, that would absorb operational continuity in any founder-departure scenario.
6.7  Compensation Philosophy and Equity Design
Compensation philosophy at Re-Tire Lebanon balances three competing objectives: attracting and retaining talent in a brain-drain context; preserving cash for capital-expenditure and working-capital purposes; and creating long-term ownership alignment that converts employees into mission-driven contributors rather than transactional workers.
Cash compensation is positioned at the 75th percentile of the Lebanese industrial market for all production and operations roles, recognising that brain-drain dynamics make below-market compensation self-defeating. Cash compensation for the founder team is positioned at the bottom-quartile of the market for equivalent senior-management roles, reflecting the founders’ equity stake and the venture’s capital constraints. Performance bonuses comprise 5 % of net profit in any year of positive net profit, distributed against the KPI framework articulated in Section 6.5. An employee-stock-option pool of 10 % of fully diluted equity is reserved for Phase 2 and Phase 3 mid-layer hires, with four-year vesting and a one-year cliff aligned to the founder vesting schedule.
Lebanon’s new pension system under Law 319 of December 2023 (UN/ILO, 2023), which will replace the legacy End-of-Service Indemnity with a contributory monthly pension once the implementing decrees are issued, is monitored as a Phase 2 compliance evolution. Re-Tire Lebanon will adopt the new system in full alignment with the statutory rollout, with no anticipated material impact on the venture’s personnel cost line because the EOSI 8.5 % contribution rate is the structural anchor of both regimes during the transition.
6.8  Diversity, Inclusion, and the Lebanese Confessional Context
Lebanon’s confessional political structure has traditionally created hiring patterns in which firms implicitly favour particular sects, geographies, or family networks. Re-Tire Lebanon’s hiring discipline explicitly rejects this pattern, with three operational consequences. First, hiring decisions are made against documented role specifications and competency assessments rather than relationship-driven shortlisting, with at least three candidates interviewed for every position above the production-operator level. Second, gender diversity is treated as a strategic asset rather than a compliance check; the venture targets at least 30 % female representation across the full workforce by end-Year 3, recognising that the Lebanese industrial-sector default of near-zero female representation is operationally and strategically suboptimal. Third, the venture’s no-bribe policy explicitly extends to hiring: requests for hiring favours from political, confessional, or family networks are declined consistently, even at the short-term cost of network friction.
Chapter VII consolidates the legal architecture within which all of the human-resource arrangements described in this chapter operate, including the SARL structure under Lebanese Code of Commerce Law 126/2019, the labour law as amended through Decree 699/2025, and the intellectual-property regime under Resolution 2385/1924 and Law 75/1999.
Chapter VII: Legal Aspects
The Legal Aspects chapter consolidates the legal architecture of Re-Tire Lebanon, including the chosen legal structure, the permits and registrations required to operate, the contract architecture with external parties, and the intellectual-property and insurance protections that shield the venture from avoidable risk. All Lebanese legal citations refer to the Official Gazette of the Republic of Lebanon, and international standards are cited to their originating bodies. The Lebanese commercial-law context has been substantially modernised by Law No. 126 of 29 March 2019, which amended the Code of Commerce of 1942 (UN ESCWA Arab Legal Portal, 2019); the chapter is written against this modernised framework.
7.1  SARL Structure
Re-Tire Lebanon is incorporated as a Société à Responsabilité Limitée under the Lebanese Code of Commerce (Legislative Decree 304 of 24 December 1942) as modernised by Law 126 of 29 March 2019. The key parameters of the structure are as follows. Minimum capital is LBP 5,000,000 fully paid up at incorporation and deposited in a bank account in the company’s name. The three founders Michael Mrad, Paul Tabet and Tony Rayes each hold 33.33 % of the parts sociales. Parts sociales are non-negotiable to third parties without the prior approval of members representing at least 75 % of the capital, with a preemptive right to existing partners. The three founders serve jointly as gérants with a two-signature requirement above USD 25,000 in transaction value; this dual-signatory protocol mirrors the precedent documented in the Harvard Business School case on Cedar Environmental (Hsieh & Abdel Aal, 2021) and is intentionally designed to mitigate the principal-agent exposure that has historically destroyed value in Lebanese family-firm governance.
A lawyer retainer is mandatory under Lebanese law for SARLs. An external auditor is optional below the LBP 30,000,000 capital threshold but is recommended for grant-compliance reporting. Law 126/2019 also permits incorporation by a single member (single-shareholder SARL), giving the venture flexibility for future restructuring, and explicitly permits foreign ownership without local-nationality requirements at the partner level. Conversion to a Société Anonyme Libanaise (SAL) is contemplated upon scale-up beyond USD 1.5 million in annual revenue, at which point the SAL structure’s higher governance overhead is justified by the wider funding optionality it provides.
7.2  Permits and Licences
Per Decrees 8471 of 4 July 2012 (Environmental Compliance) and 8633 of 7 August 2012 (Environmental Impact Assessment), the Re-Tire Lebanon facility classifies as a Class 2 establishment under Decree 5243 of 5 April 2001, triggering an Initial Environmental Examination (IEE) rather than a full Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA), provided the site avoids Annex III sensitive areas within 500 metres of watercourses such as Nahr el Kalb or Nahr Antelias, protected coastal pine reserves, or designated residential zones. The full permit-and-registration pathway before Phase 1 commercial production launch comprises seven elements.
First, commercial registration is filed at the Commercial Registry of the relevant Mohafazat (Mount Lebanon), which creates the legal personality of the SARL and allows the venture to open a bank account, sign contracts and employ staff. Second, environmental screening and the IEE are conducted per Decree 8633/2012. Third, the Environmental Compliance Certificate is issued under Decree 8471/2012 and must be renewed every three years. Fourth, an industrial permit and classification are issued by the Ministry of Industry under Decree 8018 of 13 June 2002. Fifth, a building permit is obtained through the Order of Engineers and Architects of Beirut for any facility-modification works. Sixth, NSSF registration is completed for each employee before the first paycheck is issued. Seventh, a municipal operating licence is obtained from the relevant municipality in the Federation of Keserwan and Matn Municipalities under Decree-Law 118 of 1977. Total permit-acquisition timeline is six to nine months; total cost is USD 8,000 to 15,000 inclusive of consultants.
7.3  Law 80/2018: Integrated Solid Waste Management
Law 80 of 10 October 2018 establishes the Integrated Solid Waste Management hierarchy of reduction, reuse, sorting, recycling, composting, energy recovery and disposal, and lists end-of-life tires as a priority Extended Producer Responsibility stream in the Council for Development and Reconstruction Draft National Integrated Solid Waste Management Strategy of 2024. Implementing decrees on Extended Producer Responsibility remain pending; Re-Tire Lebanon positions early to capture first-mover advantage when operationalised. Article 29 of the law enables non-financial incentives for recycling projects, which is leveraged in IDAL discussions per Section 7.6.
7.4  Law 444/2002: Environment Protection
Law 444 of 29 July 2002 enshrines the polluter-pays, precautionary, and preventive-action principles in Article 4 of the law; establishes the Environmental Impact Assessment framework in Articles 21 and 22; and governs Re-Tire Lebanon’s environmental compliance obligations through the Environmental Compliance Certificate regime under Decree 8471/2012. The certificate is renewable every three years.
7.5  Intellectual Property Rights
Re-Tire Lebanon’s intellectual-property strategy has four components.
First, trademark registration of the brand name "Re-Tire Lebanon" (word mark and logo) is filed at the Lebanese Intellectual Property Protection Office under Resolution 2385 of 1924 and Law 75 of 3 April 1999 on Intellectual Property Rights, in Class 17 (rubber and semi-finished plastics) and Class 40 (treatment of materials and recycling services) of the Nice Classification. The registration is for ten years, renewable indefinitely, at a cost of approximately USD 700 to 1,200 per class.
Second, the mechanical recycling process itself is not patentable because it uses widely available, established technology that is well outside any novelty threshold. However, proprietary formulations for specific product applications can be protected as trade secrets through non-disclosure agreements with employees, suppliers, and partners under Article 579 of the Criminal Code and the Code of Obligations and Contracts of 1932.
Third, product certifications constitute a form of process intellectual property that is practically difficult for a competitor to replicate quickly. ISO 9001 quality-management and ISO 14001 environmental-management certifications are pursued in Phase 2 through an accredited Lebanese auditor (ISO, 2015a; ISO, 2015b).
Fourth, the brand identity itself, the cumulative reputation built through marketing, quality and customer experience, is the most valuable long-term intellectual property the venture will create. Brand-building investments are accordingly treated as creating an asset whose value accrues over time, consistent with the brand-equity perspective of Aaker (1996). International filing in GAFTA markets proceeds nationally rather than through the Madrid Protocol because Lebanon is not a Madrid Protocol member; this requires separate national applications in each target country (Saudi Arabia, UAE, Egypt, Jordan, Iraq), at an estimated USD 3,500 to 6,000 per country.
7.6  Tax Regime
The Lebanese tax envelope applicable to Re-Tire Lebanon comprises corporate income tax at 17 % on net profits, value-added tax at 11 % (with exports zero-rated and input VAT recoverable), withholding tax at 10 % on dividends, withholding tax at 8.5 % on non-resident services, capital-gains tax of 10 % on moveable assets and 15 % on immovable assets, and the NSSF employer obligation of 17 % composite (11 % sickness and maternity plus 6 % family allowances) plus end-of-service indemnity at 8.5 % uncapped, for a combined 25.5 % statutory employer load (PwC Worldwide Tax Summaries, 2025). The venture targets Investment Development Authority of Lebanon Investment Project by Zone (IPZ) Zone B classification, which provides up to 50 % corporate income tax exemption for five years under Law 360 of 16 August 2001 (IDAL, 2025).
Customs duty on imported industrial equipment under Harmonised System headings 8474 and 8479 is 2 % under IDAL incentives. Customs duty on imported raw materials is 0 %. VAT of 11 % applies at import but is recoverable. The equipment landed-cost premium over Free-On-Board price is therefore approximately 13 %, which is incorporated into the Chapter VIII capital-expenditure calculations.
