The aggregate annual premium of USD 14,350 to 30,600 equates to approximately 4.5 to 10 % of capital expenditure, elevated above developed-market benchmarks of 1 to 2 % due to tire-fire surcharges, political-violence riders required in the post-2024 Lebanese context, and limited Lebanese reinsurance capacity in the aftermath of the 2020 Beirut Port explosion. The lead carrier is Bankers Assurance, with Allianz SNA providing liability and environmental impairment liability cover, AROPE providing cargo and transport cover, and Chedid Capital Insurance Brokers acting as the placing broker.
7.8  Contractual Architecture with External Parties
The contractual architecture defines how Re-Tire Lebanon engages with the external parties on which its operations depend. Six contract families are maintained, each with a standardised template that the founder team adapts to specific counterparty terms only at the margins. First, the Customer Master Supply Agreement governs Tier-1 and Tier-2 customer relationships, with terms covering volume floors and ceilings, mesh-grade quality specifications and remediation procedures, payment terms with dual-currency clause, force-majeure provisions explicitly calibrated to the Lebanese context (banking-system disruption, political-violence events, port-closure scenarios), and dispute-resolution under Lebanese arbitration with English-language proceedings.
Second, the Supplier Tire-Procurement Agreement governs feedstock-supplier relationships across Tier-1, Tier-2 and Tier-3 supplier tiers, with terms covering pickup cadence, quality-acceptance criteria for rejected tires, no-fee or tipping-fee structures depending on supplier tier, and exclusivity provisions that protect the venture’s feedstock-aggregation discipline. Third, the Logistics Service Agreement governs the relationship with owner-operator flatbed transporters, with terms covering route definitions, service-level commitments, insurance requirements, and price-escalation triggers tied to the European diesel benchmark.
Fourth, the Equipment Purchase Agreement governs the relationships with Eldan Recycling, Forrec, and refurbishment dealers, with terms covering specification compliance, delivery and installation milestones, training and commissioning obligations, warranty coverage, and spare-parts supply commitments. Fifth, the Employment Agreement template covers all employees including the founders’ formal employment contracts, with terms aligned to Lebanese Labour Law as amended through Decree 699 of 18 July 2025, with explicit non-compete and confidentiality provisions calibrated to enforceable Lebanese practice, and with vesting schedules for employees receiving equity grants from the employee-stock-option pool. Sixth, the Confidentiality and Non-Disclosure Agreement template covers all external counterparty relationships in which the venture shares operational, financial, or strategic information, including grant-funder due-diligence engagements, potential investor conversations, and joint-development discussions with downstream compounder partners.
7.9  Regulatory-Compliance Calendar and Renewal Discipline
Regulatory compliance is not a one-time event at incorporation but an ongoing operational discipline throughout the venture’s life. Re-Tire Lebanon maintains a regulatory-compliance calendar that enumerates every regulatory obligation, the renewal frequency, the responsible founder, and the lead time required to begin renewal preparation.
Annual obligations include the SARL annual general meeting and audited financial statement filing under Articles 109 and 132 of the Lebanese Code of Commerce, the Ministry of Industry industrial-permit renewal, the municipal commercial-licence renewal, and the NSSF annual reconciliation. Triennial obligations include the Environmental Compliance Certificate renewal under Decree 8471/2012, the Initial Environmental Examination update if facility scope changes, and the Lebanese Civil Defence fire-safety certification renewal per NFPA Chapter 33. Variable-frequency obligations include IDAL IPZ incentive-package compliance reporting tied to project-implementation milestones, EU and UNDP grant-cycle compliance reporting tied to award terms, and Banque du Liban Circular 158 compliance reporting if the venture uses the deposit-recovery facilities.
Compliance discipline is maintained through three practices. First, a designated compliance owner, Paul Tabet in his Chief Operating Officer role, holds explicit accountability for every calendar item with no shared or rotating ownership. Second, 90-day forward visibility is maintained on every renewal deadline, ensuring that no obligation is approached without adequate preparation time. Third, an annual external compliance audit is conducted by the venture’s retained Beirut law firm, providing an independent verification that no obligation has been missed and that all renewals are current.
